<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Supports Sudan's Bid for U.N. Security Council Membership </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa said on Monday that Egypt supports Sudan's bid to become a
member of the United Nations Security Council next year.
</P>
<P>
A consensus has been reached among the African and Arab
countries in favor of Khartoum's efforts to secure Africa's seat in
the Security Council, Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will vote for Sudan, out of respect for bilateral
relations and the African-Arab decision, he was quoted as saying by
Egypt's official Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the attempt by the United States to prevent Sudan
from becoming a Council member, Moussa said that every country has
a right to adopt a stance in line with its interests.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is lobbying to stop Sudan from getting the seat, saying
it is "an unsuitable candidate" because it is under U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council imposed sanctions on Sudan in 1996
for failing to produce suspects in the 1995 attempt on the life of
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Addis Ababa, Ethiopia. Sudan
has denied charges that it masterminded the assassination attempt.
It has also normalized the relations with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Egypt, Ethiopia and all council members except the United
States believe the sanctions should now be lifted. Washington has
asked the Council to defer a decision on the embargoes until mid-
November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The first metro line in Istanbul, Turkey's largest
city, opened over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
The 683 million U.S. dollar line, linking two main business
districts, runs for 8.5 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
The metro line can carry up 70,000 passengers an hour in each
direction and is built to withstand earthquakes of 9.0 on the
Richter scale.
</P>
<P>
A consortium made up of French company Alstom and local
contractors started the construction in 1992.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- A creation area, Kordon Sunset, in Izmir, Turkey's
third largest city, was opened over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit inaugurated the 35 million U.S.
dollar Kordon Sunset, which turned out to be one of the world's
most expensive recreation areas.
</P>
<P>
The 150-acre seaside area now features Izmir city landmarks --
the Korak Clock Tower and the Izmir Fair. Special events will also
be staged in the area.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The increasing oil price is expected to cost Turkey to
pay 5 billion U.S. dollars for crude oil imports this year,
reported the Anatolia News Agency on Monday.
</P>
<P>
According to the calculations of the State Planning Organization
(DPT), Turkey paid 25.8 dollars for one barrel of oil in the first
six months of 2000, compared to 12.5 dollars in the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
The price of one barrel of crude oil has increased by 108.1
percent for Turkey in one year.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- A senior Iranian official on Monday urged the
government to lower the tariffs on ship registration to attract
more ships to register in Iran.
</P>
<P>
If Iran reduces the ceiling of the tariffs on ship registration,
more international ship owners would register their ships in Iran,
said Deputy Minister of Road and Transport Mokhtar Kalantari.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, Iran charges 5-10 percent of the
ship's price for registration while the tariff is lower in other
countries, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The cost of registering ships in Iran is so high that even
Iranian ship owners prefer to register their ships in other
countries, the official said.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Some 1,200 firms from more than 70 foreign countries
are to participate in the 26th Tehran International Trade Fair,
which is to be held from October 1-8.
</P>
<P>
The participating countries will include 31 from Asia, 25 from
Europe, 10 from Africa, five from America and one from Oceania,
Hussein Qassemi, managing director of Iran's International Fairs
Company, was quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency as saying
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The total exhibition area will be more than 90,000 square
meters, the official said, adding that the biggest pavilions will
belong to Germany, Japan and Italy respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
