<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Host Conference on Curbing Illegal Diamonds Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Ministers from diamond
producing countries are to meet in Pretoria of South Africa on
Tuesday to discuss how to stamp out illegal sales of the gems
fueling different conflicts in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the conference is to protect the legitimate
trade of "clean diamonds", and stop that of the dirty ones, South
Africa's Department of Trade and Industry said in a statement
published on Monday.
</P>
<P>
At least 10 foreign ministers and 150 delegates from the
diamond industry are expected to attend the three-day event, to be
hosted by the South African Department of Trade and Industry, said
the conference's co-ordinator Jeremy Mndaweni.
</P>
<P>
According to him, the United Nations envoy Paul Heinbecker is
expected to address the meeting on what a role the world body is
to play in severing the link between the precious stone and wars
in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He said countries to be represented include Sierra Leone, the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), Angola, Namibia, Botswana,
Belgium, the United States, Zambia, and Britain.
</P>
<P>
Diamond trade in countries like Angola, Sierra Leone and the
DRC has long been playing a role in funding civil wars. The
Western countries led by Britain and the U.S. recently accused
Liberia of helping channeling out diamonds produced in areas
controlled by Sierra Leone's rebels, thus prolonging the conflict
in the West African country.
</P>
<P>
The "conflict diamonds", dubbed for diamonds funding conflicts
in Africa, account for at least 4 percent of the total diamond
trade volume of 6.8 billion U. S. dollars annually, said Mndaweni.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
