<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Urges U.S. to Abide by 1972 Treaty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taking the floor at the annual general debate of the U.N.
General Assembly, the foreign minister said Russia will introduce
a draft General Assembly resolution in support of the ABM treaty.
</P>
<P>
START III, or the third round of Strategic Arms Reduction
treaty, aims at lowering nuclear warheads of the two countries to
1,500 units, after START II enters into force. Russia's State Duma
ratified START II in April this year.
</P>
<P>
Under START II, the U.S. and Russia must cut the number of
nuclear warheads from 6,000 to no more than 3.500 on each side by
2007. The two countries agreed in 1997 to start their third round
of talks once START II enters into force.
</P>
<P>
Russian-U.S. consultations on strategic stability issues have
been held regularly since February 1999, but the two parties have
not been able to reach an agreement on the destiny of the 1972 ABM
treaty.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said the notions of sovereignty and territorial
integrity of states are still very much alive.
</P>
<P>
"Disregard for these principles as well as military
intervention in circumvention of the U.N. Security Council, under
whatever humanitarian pretexts, undermine the very foundations of
the world order and pave the way to arbitrariness in international
affairs," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
