<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain's Liberal Democrat Leader Calls for Fuel Tax Cap </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
He pledged his party would tax oil companies' excess profits if
they failed to ensure fuel supplies.
</P>
<P>
Kennedy was making an emergency statement on the fuel crisis at
his party's annual conference in the southern seaside city of
Bournemouth.
</P>
<P>
"Fuel tax policy has to be fair -- if it's not, it won't work.
Let's be upfront about the environmental agenda," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Lib Dem leader also called on the government to take the
following measures:
</P>
<P>
-- Cap fuel taxes for five years in real terms so it would not
profit from future increases in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
-- Use the value added tax windfall received from the higher-
than-expected fuel price to ease the burden on the traveling
public.
</P>
<P>
-- Ensure oil companies recognize their social responsibilities
in terms of price and supply security.
</P>
<P>
-- And support people in rural communities who rely on fuel,
for example by providing rate relief on rural fuel stations and
investment in public transport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
