<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombia Condemns Mass Kidnapping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Colombian Vice President
Gustavo Bell Lemus condemned Monday the kidnapping of 45 people by
the National Liberation Army (ELN) in western Colombia.
</P>
<P>
The vice president, who opened Monday a seminar on the Human
Rights and Military Criminal Law in Cartagena, coastal city of
this Caribbean country, said the matter is a flagrant violation of
basic rights.
</P>
<P>
"The ELN's action is a fact that shows this rebel group's scorn
to the rules of the International Humanitarian Law," said the vice
president.
</P>
<P>
"This kidnapping is a contradiction at these moments when the
ELN holds peace talks with the government," said Bell Lemus in his
speech.
</P>
<P>
Besides, Director of the National Police Gen. Luis Ernesto
Gilibert Vargas revealed Monday that the guerrilla group kidnapped
45 people Sunday some 18 kilometers southwest of Cali, capital of
the state of Valle del Cauca, on the road that links this city
with Buenaventura, the main Colombian harbor in the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
Over half of the hostages were released a few hours after the
kidnapping, while the liberation of the rest will take place in
the months to come, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
