<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Time Short for Palestinians, Israelis to Reach Peace Deal: Moussa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa warned on Monday that time was running out for the
Palestinians and Israelis to reach a peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
Under the current situation, there are still the possibilities
of success or failure for a peace deal, Moussa told reporters. But
the lack of time was not in favor of the success of an agreement,
he was quoted as saying by the state-run Middle East News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israelis are under pressure to hammer out a
deal as the Israeli parliament, which is threatening to topple
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's minority government, will reconvene in
late October after summer recess. And the presidential elections of
the United States, the major sponsor of the peace process, will
also take place in November.
</P>
<P>
Moussa called for intensive negotiations between the two sides,
saying that sufficient opportunity must be given for the efforts
exerted by all parties to bear fruit, especially in the coming few
weeks up to the end of October.
</P>
<P>
He said that no agreement has been made on any of the matters on
the table, including Jerusalem, Palestinian refugees and final
borders, and that requires work to be focused in the short time
remaining.
</P>
<P>
Ideas put forward recently of placing parts of Jerusalem under
international sovereignty will apply only to the city's holy
places, he said. He reiterated that the Palestinians should have
full sovereignty over East Jerusalem as a whole and there is no
doubt about that.
</P>
<P>
Control over Jerusalem and its holy places has been the main
stumbling block in forging a final peace deal between the
Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Moussa, who returned to Cairo on Saturday from the United
States, where he attended the United Nations Millennium Summit and
the General Assembly, said Egypt was continuing its contacts with
all parties to try to advance the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Road Accident Kills 21 People in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A total of 21 people died on
Monday in a traffic accident in east Turkey on Monday, reported the
Anatolia News Agency.
</P>
<P>
The disaster took place at the junction linking Susuz township
of eastern Kars province and Gole township of eastern Ardahan
province where a lorry and a minibus collided with an oncoming
truck.
</P>
<P>
Twelve people were killed on the spot while the injured were
rushed to hospital. The death toll swelled to 21 after some
critically injured people failed emergency treatment.
</P>
<P>
Two people still remain hospitalized in critical conditions.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long suffered from fatal traffic accidents. Over the
past decade, such accidents have claimed 60,000 lives and seriously
injured or disabled 1 million people, according to official
statistics.
</P>
<P>
As the number of fatal traffic accidents are sharply on the
rise, the parliament is expected to take up the issue for debate
when it reconvenes in October after a three-month summer recess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
