<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Cabinet Endorses 2001 Budget Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli cabinet announced
Monday evening that it had approved the Finance Ministry's budget
bill for the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
After seven-hour marathon debate, nine government ministers
voted in favor of the budget draft, while acting Interior Minister
Haim Ramon and Science, Culture and Sports Minister Matan Vilnai
voted against it, according to a cabinet statement issued after the
weekly meeting.
</P>
<P>
Three other ministers, including acting Foreign Minister Shlomo
Ben-Ami who was still not back from the United Nations General
Assembly, abstained in the voting.
</P>
<P>
Addressing his ministers, Prime Minister Ehud Barak said that
the budget bill, which includes expenditures of 197 billion shekels
(about 49 billion U.S. dollars), will further boost the economic
development and narrow the social gap between "haves and have-
nots."
</P>
<P>
Barak rejected criticism inside and outside his cabinet that the
budget did not do enough to bridge the social gulf, citing as
evidence the increased funds allocated for education and
infrastructure building.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the defense budget slash, Barak admitted that the
cut in the defense budget is not nominal and is very painful, but
added that in light of existing conditions, there is no choice. He
said that he agreed to the budget cut after calculated the risks.
</P>
<P>
But Israel Defense Forces' Chief of General Staff Shaul Mofaz,
who recently developed a chilly relation with Barak, retorted that
the defense establishment needs a larger budget in order to meet
the army's working plans.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Yossi Beilin also urged the prime minister to
direct more budget money to the Arab sector in Israel, which Beilin
claimed has been deprived for 52 years since the establishment of
the Jewish state in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Beilin stressed that the time has come for the government to
take the necessary steps to bring the situation to an end.
</P>
<P>
The budget bill is now ready to be presented to the Knesset
(parliament), which is scheduled to end its summer recess and
reconvene at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary debate of the budget will be a tough political
test for Barak, whose coalition now controls only one-third seats
of the 120-member Knesset. Some opposition factions had already
expressed their dissatisfaction with the bill.
</P>
<P>
Natan Sharansky, former interior minister and leader of the
Yisrael Ba'aliya party, had proposed a no-confidence motion against
Barak on the budget.
</P>
<P>
The Likud termed the budget bill as "social apathy," saying that
the government has approved a budget which will hurt the health and
education systems and several sectors of the population,such as the
elders, recently-discharged soldiers and young couples. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
