<HEADLINE> Eight Muslim Brotherhood Members Detained in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Egypt on Monday placed eight
members of the outlawed Muslim Brotherhood under two-week detention
in Alexandria for enquiry, the state-run Middle East News Agency
(MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
Director of East Alexandria Prosecution Ibrahim al Saadani, who
ordered the detention, accused the eight of joining an illegal
organization and propagating the movement's ideas which threat
social peace and security.
</P>
<P>
The eight detainees were among the 15 Brotherhood members who
were arrested in the Mediterranean port city last Wednesday, Friday
and Saturday. But MENA did not specify what has happened to the
others.
</P>
<P>
Arrests and releases of members of the banned but partly
tolerated Muslim Brotherhood have increased in recent months.
Activists of the group have accused the authorities of intimidating
them and trying to stop them from taking part in the parliamentary
elections due in October and November.
</P>
<P>
The Brotherhood, founded in 1928 and banned in 1954, says
publicly that it advocates an Islamic state through peaceful means.
But the authorities accused the group of encouraging violence
through collaborating with Islamist militant groups and have been
cracking down on it since 1995.
</P>
<P>
Many members of the movement, who cannot run for the parliament,
the People's Assembly, on a Brotherhood ticket, have reportedly
decided to stand as independents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
