<HEADLINE> Israeli Truckers Threaten to Block Roads over Fuel Price Hike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Israeli truck drivers have
decided to block national roads on Tuesday if no agreement is
reached with the government on fuel price reduction.
</P>
<P>
Israel Road Transport Board (IRTB) representatives will hold the
last meeting Monday evening with officials of the Ministries of
Finance and Transport to discuss the fuel price issue.
</P>
<P>
If the two sides failed to reach an agreement, then truckers and
bus drivers will begin road blocks at 6:00 a.m. (0300 GMT) on
Tuesday, IRTB said.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Heavy truck, bus and taxi drivers will at first
move their vehicles only at 30-40 kilometers per hour on the
national high way between Haifa in the north of the country and
Ashdod just north of the Gaza Strip on Tuesday, but all road
junctions along this highway will not be closed, IRTB said.
</P>
<P>
IRTB has members of some 15,000 heavy truck drivers and 4,000
bus drivers. Over 90 percent of the cargoes are transported by
trucks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Due to oil price increases on the world market, the Ministries
of Finance and Transport decided to increase fuel prices in the
country since Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The price of diesel fuel has been increased by 13 percent,
bringing the price for diesel to 2.41 shekels (0.60 U.S. dollars) a
liter. Since the beginning of 1999, diesel price has been increased
by nearly 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
The police said they recognize the trucker's rights to organize
a legitimate protest, but would not hesitate to take legal actions
against those who break the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
