<HEADLINE> Lebanese Officials to Visit Cyprus to Discuss Immigrant Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A two-member delegation of the
Lebanese Ministry of Emigrant Affairs will arrive in Nicosia
Tuesday to solve the differences on immigrant issue between the two
countries, it was reported here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 266 illegal immigrants, mainly of Arab and Kurdish origin,
were saved from drowning last week by the Cyprus authorities when
their boat sank off the western island. They are now on two Cyprus
ships in the Limassol port, on the island's southern coast.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus authorities claimed that the immigrants have set off
from Lebanon for Greece or Italy and wants them to be repatriated.
The Lebanese authorities, however, refused to take in these
immigrants, saying there is no evidence that the boat had sailed
from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus Interior Minister Christodoulos Christodoulou said Monday

that the two Lebanese officials will be having talks on the issue
with the relevant Cypriot officials.
</P>
<P>
He said the Cyprus government has undisputable evidence that the
boat carrying the illegal immigrants had sailed from a Lebanese
port.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus and Lebanon signed an agreement in 1999 providing that
illegal immigrants showing up on their shores must be returned if
there is evidence proving the port from which they leave.
</P>
<P>
Due to the unique geographical location, Cyprus' shores have
been a major transit for illegal immigrants from the Middle East to
European countries. Some seek political asylum and many are conned
by foreigners who promise to take them elsewhere. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
