<HEADLINE> Former U.N. Humanitarian Coordinator Visits Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tareq Aziz on Monday held talks with Hans Von Sponeck, former U.N.
humanitarian coordinator who is now in Iraq again for a visit.
</P>
<P>
Aziz highly evaluated Sponeck's work when he acted as the U.N.
humanitarian coordinator in Iraq, as well as his efforts to
acquaint the world with the crippling impacts of the decade-old U.
N. sanctions on Iraq, the official Iraqi News Agency (INA)
reported.
</P>
<P>
Aziz also briefed Sponeck about Iraq's current humanitarian
situation.
</P>
<P>
For his part, Sponeck said that the international community is
increasingly aware of the "disastrous" effect of the sanctions, and
the international efforts to lift the sanctions are mounting, the
INA said.
</P>
<P>
Sponeck resigned his post to protest the U.N. sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
A decade of sanctions against Iraq has "completely failed" and a
new approach is called for, Sponeck said in July.
</P>
<P>
Describing the situation for civilians in Iraq as "critical," he
listed the diseases -- diarrhea, respiratory problems and
malnutrition-- from which Iraqis, especially children, are
suffering.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.N. oil-for-food is not working. Under the deal,
introduced at the end of 1996, Iraq is allowed to sell oil in order
to purchase essential goods under strict U.N. supervision.
</P>
<P>
Before he left his post at the end of last March, Iraqi
President Saddam Hussein met him and expressed appreciation for his
stance.
</P>
<P>
It has been reported that the Iraqi president promised Sponeck
that he can visit Iraq at any time and need no visa.
</P>
<P>
Sponeck, who was appointed as the top relief official in Iraq in
October 1998, angered the United States and Britain by saying that
the U.N. Security Council should treat Iraq's humanitarian needs
separately from the Council's aim to monitor Baghdad's disarmament.
</P>
</TEXT>
