<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Calls for Much More World Attention to African Problems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The appeal came as Ethiopian Foreign Minister Seyoum Mesfin
took the floor at the two-week general debate of the 55th General
Assembly session, which began here a week ago.
</P>
<P>
The problems of Africa "are defined by those two very closely
related challenges. Africa's development continues to be arrested
by problems of insecurity, instability and lack of peace," he said.
"On the other hand, it appears unrealistic to expect durable peace
in Africa without hope in the future that could be brought about
only by visible indications about possibilities for progress."
</P>
<P>
"In both areas, Africa has not had the necessary support
commensurate with the complexity of the challenges it has faced,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is far from the truth that Africa has enjoyed sustained,
resolute and all-out support, either in the area of economic
development or in the sphere of peace and security," he said.
</P>
<P>
He is echoing remarks by African leaders at the September 6-8
Millennium Summit that Africa needs quick and substantial support
in its efforts to stop conflicts, promote economic and social
development and check the spread of AIDS disease. The African
leaders blamed Western industrialized countries for double
standards or paying lip service in the area of the official
development assistance (ODA) to Africa, which has been on decline
over the past years.
</P>
<P>
"We have indeed been encouraged by the well-deserved emphasis
that was given to Africa and to Africa's predicament at the
Millennium Summit," he said. "It is our hope that the summit may
have helped create greater determination for cooperation with the
peoples of Africa so that Africa may make real progress in
addressing the challenges of development, and of peace and
security."
</P>
<P>
"But Africa's fate has been different," he said. "For whatever
reason, it has been easier to lose hope on Africa, than to give
the continent the benefit of the doubt."
</P>
<P>
On its border conflict with Eritrea, the Ethiopian foreign
minister said, "We are proceeding with full commitment to put
behind us the crisis we have had with Eritrea."
</P>
<P>
"Even before the deployment of peacekeepers, contrary to
experience in other places, the cessation of hostilities has held
for months now," he said. 
</P>
