<HEADLINE> UK Holiday Companies Hit by Soaring Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Over the past 12 months, airline jet fuel costs have risen by
more than 90 percent in dollar terms, from 130 U.S. dollars to 250
dollars per metric tone.
</P>
<P>
It is generally believed here that the price increase could
pose a serious threat to tour operators, such as Airtours, Thomson
Travel and First Choice, all of whom operate their own airline.
</P>
<P>
Nigel Reed, of BNP Paribas, said: "There is little these
companies can do to offset this massive increase in fuel costs."
</P>
<P>
Most of them were already operating at close to full capacity,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The full impact of the fuel hikes is unlikely to be felt for
several months, as companies tend to hedge in advance to help
protect themselves against price fluctuations.
</P>
<P>
However, the trend for higher fuel prices provides a fresh blow
for travel groups, which are already battling with a slump in
European demand and aggressive discounting. 
