<HEADLINE> Former U.S. President Stresses One China Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. President
Jimmy Carter said there is only one China in the world and he
hoped that the Taiwan issue would be resolved peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Carter made the remarks while meeting with Zeng Jianhui, member
of the Standing Committee of China's National People's Congress (
NPC) and chairman of the NPC Foreign Affairs Committee at his
native town of Plains, Georgia, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The former president called on the U.S. and China to strengthen
their cooperation and enhance their exchanges in the new century.
</P>
<P>
Recalling his talks with the late Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping
about normalization of diplomatic relations between the U.S. and
China, Carter said that both sides maintained that there was only
one China in the world and Taiwan was part of China.
</P>
<P>
All the U.S. administrations have since then abided by the One
China principle, he added.
</P>
<P>
Jimmy Carter was U.S. President from 1977 to 1981. After
leaving the White House, Carter returned to Georgia, where he
founded the nonprofit Carter Center in 1982 in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Jianhui, who led a seven-member NPC delegation on a two-
week visit to the United States, expressed his gratitude for
Carter's contribution in promoting the development of bilateral
relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese NPC delegation arrived in the United States on
September 9 at the invitation of the U.S. Institute of
Representative Government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece Rejects Turkish Call for Dialog on Aegean Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Greece Monday once again
rejected Turkey's call for direct talks on Aegean issues and urged
the neighboring country to make real steps for a rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
Greece recognized no difference with Turkey apart from that of
the delineation for the Aegean continental shelf, Greek government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas said at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the request made by Turkish Prime Minister
Bullet Ecevit last Saturday for a dialog with Greece in order to
find a just settlement regarding the Aegean disputes.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting Ecevit's call for direct talks, Reppas said that
such statements had no receiver because all other issues were
already clear.
</P>
<P>
As for the recent meeting between the foreign ministers of the
two countries in New York, he said that there had been "positive
elements" and "a constructive contribution" to relations between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman stressed that Turkey must move in the right
direction because it had so far failed to contribute decisively to
improving Greek and Turkish relations.
</P>
<P>
For decades, Greece and Turkey, both NATO members, have
closely gone to war three times over their territorial disputes in
the eastern Aegean Sea and the Cyprus problem, but they have since
last June to take steps to improve their strained relations by
holding several rounds of bilateral talks and signing a total of
nine agreements for bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
With the politically improvement in Greek-Turkish ties, the
trade between the two countries have also increased significantly,
and the bilateral trade volume in the first half of this year have
risen to 491.6 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Although the relations between the two neighbors have shown
some improvement, Greece has complained that Turkey has not done
enough for the rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
Greece has insisted that only one issue, namely the
delineation of the Aegean continental shelf, needs settlement, and
calls on Turkey to take it up with the International Court at The
Hague. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
