<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana Calls for Firm International Legal Framework </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The appeal came as Ghana's Foreign Minister James Victor Gbeho
took the floor at the two-week general debate of the 55th General
Assembly session, which began here on September 12.
</P>
<P>
"Ghana believes that the efforts of the United Nations to
promote and maintain international peace and security should rest
on a firm international legal framework, hence the need to
maintain support for the useful work being done by the
International Law Commission and related institutions in the U.N.
system," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the tremendous progress made in the
establishment of legal frameworks for the pursuit of crimes
against humanity for example must continue if our societies are to
be maintained," he said.
</P>
<P>
"In the particular case of Africa, support for the
International Criminal Court is not only desirable," he said. "It
is a must, since censure by the international community is now
very necessary in dissuading warlords and rebels from committing
the heinous crimes that we continue to witness in countries such
as Sierra Leone, Rwanda, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo,
" he said.
</P>
<P>
"Ghana recommends, therefore, that international law should
ensure that there is punishment for perpetrators of such crimes
and also that they do not enjoy amnesty from all countries," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"The spirit of compromise, which led to the overwhelming
endorsement of the Rome Treaty of the International Criminal Court,
must be kept alive to our objectives in this field," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is taking an uphill effort to get into
effect the treaty creating the International Criminal Court.
</P>
<P>
So far, 112 countries have signed the treaty, and 19 countries
have ratified. At least 60 countries must ratify before the treaty
can enter into force.
</P>
<P>
The United States was one of the seven countries voting "no"
when 120 countries meeting in Rome in June 1998 approved the
tribunal, which would have jurisdiction over genocide, war crimes
and crimes against humanity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Insists on Claims to Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 18 (Xinhua)-- Israeli Acting Foreign
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami Monday called for an "ideal compromise"
with the Palestinians over their long-standing disputes, while
giving no sign of backing off from its claims to Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 55th session of the U.N. General Assembly, the
Israeli official said: "Peace is not about twisting each other's
arms, it is about defining a common interest. I believe that such
an ideal compromise is not impossible to achieve, while banishing
the sword from this Land of God."
</P>
<P>
However, he stressed that even at the height of "the Golden Age,
" "our people never abandoned their dream of, and yearning for
Jerusalem."
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami apparently echoed Prime Minister Ehud Barak who ruled
out hours earlier Islamic sovereignty over a key Jerusalem shrine
sacred to Muslims and Jews, and closed the door to a Palestinian
compromise proposal.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side, insisting on sovereignty over
traditionally Arab east Jerusalem, has proposed to consider the
option that the Islamic world's Jerusalem Committee exert
sovereignty over the Haram as-Sharif, Temple Mount as Jews call.
</P>
<P>
Barak told his cabinet members that "Israel is not only opposed
to transferring sovereignty on the Temple Mount to the
Palestinians, but it is also absolutely opposed to transferring
sovereignty on the Mount to any Muslim body," according to reports
from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Hours later, the acting foreign minister told the General
Assembly session that the Jewish holy sites and shrines in
Jerusalem were "the very heart of the Jewish faith, identity and
history."
</P>
<P>
The issue of Jerusalem, the main dispute over who should be
sovereign on the holy compound, the holiest shrine of Judaism and
home to two major mosques, hindered progress in the July Camp
David Israeli-Palestinian negotiations and the latest contacts
resumed in New York and Jerusalem in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
"Just as we do not question the sincerity of the sentiments of
others toward their holy sites in Jerusalem, we expect that others
will not question the Jewish people's deep, awesome attachment to
Jerusalem and its holy sites -- from which we will never again be
parted," said Ben-Ami, who said a deal with the Palestinians was
not promising last week.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has responded to Barak's
latest statement by saying Monday that it was not up to Israel to
decide who will be sovereign over the Old City's shrines. "It is a
Muslim, Christian and Arab decision," he insisted.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side is scheduled to speak at the U.N. General
Assembly session Tuesday to further elaborate the Palestinian
stands on the thorny issues. In the meantime, the Israeli and
Palestinian negotiators would resume talks later Monday in
Jerusalem with no sign of immediate progress in sight.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli acting foreign minister also touched another
thorny issue, the return of Palestinian refugees, at the U.N.
session. He said the problem was "largely the inevitable by-
product of Arab and Jewish fears and the protracted bitter
fighting" and a future Palestinian state should provide for the
vindication of the Palestinian claim for the right of return.
</P>
<P>
"Israel has expressed its willingness to actively participate
in any international effort and fund aimed at providing the
financial foundations for the resolution of the refugee problem.
Out of humanitarian considerations, Israel may also accept a small
and very limited number of refugees within a scheme of family
reunification," Ben-Ami said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has asked Israel to let the Palestinian
exiles return home and compensate them for their losses. It needs
time and hard negotiations to narrow their gaps.
</P>
<P>
The both sides were awaiting the United States to submit its
bridging proposal. President Bill Clinton has set the Middle East
peace process as one of his main diplomatic goals in his last days
at White House. U.S. presidential elections are scheduled for
November. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
