<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Strongly Condemns Murder of U.N. Worker in Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The condemnation was contained in a statement issued by Annan's
spokesman after the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR)
said in Geneva Monday that one worker was killed Sunday and
another still missing in an attack by unidentified gunmen in
southeast Guinea, near the border with Liberia.
</P>
<P>
Annan "strongly condemns this senseless violence against
humanitarian workers, and appeals to West Africa leaders to do
whatever they can to secure the release of Ms. Laurence Djeya,"
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general is shocked by the murder of Mensah
Kpognon, the head of the sub-office of the U.N. High Commissioner
for Refugees in Macenta, Guinea, yesterday," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"He is also extremely concerned over the fate of another UNHCR
staff member, Sapeu Laurence Djeya, who was abducted by the same
unidentified armed elements who murdered Kpognon," the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general conveys his condolences to Kpognon
family as well as to the UNHCR staff who are still mourning the
death of three colleagues killed in West Timor only two weeks ago,
" the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The killed man, a Togolese national, is the fourth UNHCR staff
member murdered this month. The three others were killed in a pro-
Indonesian militia attack in West Timor on September 6.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva-based U.N. agency said it is calling on aid workers
worldwide to hold marches on Thursday to protest the abduction and
recent killings of UNHCR staff.
</P>
<P>
Several Guineans were killed and many houses burnt down in the
attack, which began early Sunday morning, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
There are more than 460,000 refugees in Guinea -- about 330,000
of them Sierra Leonean and some 126,000 Liberian. Most of the
refugees in the Macenta area are Liberian, UNHCR said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
