<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Khatami Highlights Freedom of Thought for Iranians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Iran's reform-minded President
Mohammad Khatami stressed on Monday that the people should enjoy
the freedom of thought, which is the basis of democracy.
</P>
<P>
The basis of democracy is sovereignty of people over their fate,
and without freedom of thought, democracy cannot be realized,
Khatami told a public gathering in West Azarbaijan province in
northwestern Iran, where he is on an inspection tour.
</P>
<P>
The president also called for "unity and unanimity of views"
among the Iranian people, the official IRNA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said the people should be united in resisting both pressures
from outside and the "narrow-minded stances" at home.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, who won the 1997 presidential election as an advocate
of social, cultural and political reforms, has announced that he
will seek a second term in the presidential election next year.
</P>
<P>
But he and his reformist allies are facing increasing pressure
from the conservatives who are determined to safeguard by all means
their strict Islamic rule established since the 1979 Islamic
revolution.
</P>
<P>
The conservatives, who control the judiciary, the military and
many other key state organs, have stepped up crackdown on the
reformist campaign.
</P>
<P>
More than 20 pro-reform newspapers and periodicals have been
closed and several reformist journalists imprisoned by the
conservative judiciary on charges of violating Islamic principles
and advocating pro-American reforms.
</P>
<P>
The reformist camp under Khatami has maintained restraint to
prevent the situation from spinning out of control, which many
believe would only benefit the conservatives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
