<HEADLINE> Pak to Boost Trade With Neighbors via North </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GILGIT, Pakistan, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Chief
Executive General Pervez Musharraf Monday said his government was
taking concrete steps for the development of northern areas for
boosting its trade with China and Central Asian states.
</P>
<P>
"We intend to open this region for our trade with China and
Central Asian republics," he said while talking to participants of
the Silk Route Festival at the newly-inaugurated Lalak Jan Stadium
in Gilgit.
</P>
<P>
He said the government plans to lay a network of roads linking
Chitral, Hunza, Skardu, Chilas and other parts of northern areas
to promote tourism and trade activities in the region.
</P>
<P>
General Musharraf said his government is doing its best to
attract foreign tourists to this picturesque area of Pakistan.He
said promotion of tourism would also contribute to the
socioeconomic development of northern areas.
</P>
<P>
Northern areas are where three gigantic mountains -- the
Himalayas, Karakoran and Hindukush -- converge and boast lots of
scenic beauty. The old Silk Route connected China and the Middle
East and Europe through this mountainous area.
</P>
<P>
During the past week, cultural troupes from China, Iran,
Afghanistan and Jordan and from all the four provinces of Pakistan
and different districts of northern areas performed at the Silk
Route Festival. 
</P>
