<HEADLINE> Laos Hit by Serious Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Many days of successive and
heavy rain caused the Mekong River, Sebangphay River and other
rivers in Khammouane Province of Central Laos to rise and more
than 22,000 hectares of paddy fields were flooded, official Lao
news agency KPL reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Khammouane Province has been affected by flood since September
8 and more than 20,800 hectares of the flooding areas have been
damaged.
</P>
<P>
At present 138 schools have to be temporary closed because of
the flood. Land traffic has also been cut off between the
districts of Thakhek and Nongbok and local people could only
travel by boat.
</P>
<P>
Heavy rains and a number of storms have also caused serious
floods in Champassak Province.
</P>
<P>
The water levels of the Mekong River at Pakse district,
Champassak Province, were measured at 12.81 meters on September 12,
higher than the dangerous level.
</P>
<P>
KPL quoted deputy head Khampong Sanainphone of Champassak
Province's Agriculture and Forestry Service as saying more than 13,
724 hectares of rice fields have been damaged in 461 villages and
nearly 10,200 houses submerged.
</P>
<P>
However, there has been no report of deaths so far. 
</P>
</TEXT>
