<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Political Parties Urged to Settle Disputes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A European parliamentary
delegation now on a visit to Bangladesh Monday urged the political
parties in the country to sit down and settle their dispute to
pave the way for the return of the boycotting opposition to the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
"The delegation had talks with both the ruling party and the
opposition and urged both sides to seek a solution of their
dispute so that opposition parties can return to the parliament
and take part in proceedings," the EU envoy in Dhaka, Antonio De
Menezes, said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The visit of the two-member delegation coincided with the start
of preparations for election in Bangladesh amid strained relations
between the ruling Awami League and the opposition alliance led by
Bangladesh Nationalist party.
</P>
<P>
The opposition has been boycotting the parliament session for
over a year, alleging that their leaders and lawmakers were not
given enough time in the parliament to talk about problems of the
people. But the speaker of the parliament has rejected the
opposition claim.
</P>
<P>
Jeaqim Miranda, chairman of the EU Committee on Development and
Cooperation, and Bob Van den Bos, the committee's rapporteur for
Bangladesh, are now in Bangladesh on a five-day visit at the
invitation of Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to interfere in Bangladesh's politics, but we
have been asked to monitor the next general election to be held
next year," Miranda told a discussion at the Bangladesh Institute
of International Strategic Studies.
</P>
<P>
The EU team also visited the country's Chittagong Hill tracts
and held talks there with former rebel leaders who had been at
guerrilla war with the government for over two decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
