<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundian Tutsi Group Threatens to Bomb Refugee Camps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- An unknown Burundi
Tutsi extremist group has threatened to start bombing Burundian
refugee camps in western Tanzania next month, the independent
Guardian newspaper reported here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bombing is set to start on October 15, Anti Hutu Revolution
Burundi Group (AHRBG), was quoted as saying in a secret letter
written to D.G. Ludamila, the Police Commander of Ngara District
in Tanzania's western Kagera Region, which hosts hundreds of
thousands of Burundian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The group said it has already planted land mines close to camps
currently sheltering about 450,000 refugees, adding that apart
from land mines, the terrorist group possesses hand grenades for
the planned attacks, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Kigoma Regional Police Commander Placid Chaka said over the
weekend the movement of refugees and foreigners in the two regions
is being closely monitored by law enforcers, adding that stern
measures would be taken against any person or group suspected to
belong to such a terrorist gang.
</P>
<P>
The letter says that such attacks are necessary for "the
failure of Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa to repatriate all
Burundian refugees back home as soon as possible".
</P>
<P>
"We requested President Mkapa to repatriate all Burundian
refugees back home similar to the 1996 repatriation of Rwandan
refugees. But, to date, he has done nothing," reads the letter.
</P>
<P>
"The AHRBG wants to destroy and wage an underground war against
any country, including Tanzania, which offers accommodation to
refugees of Hutu origin who used to launch military attacks
against our country," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
The terrorist group also charges that it is not in support of
the Peace and Reconciliation Agreement signed in Arusha last month
by Burundi parties and possible involvement of armed rebel groups,
mainly CNDD-FDD, in the planned cease-fire negotiations scheduled
to start later this month, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In Burundi, fighting between the army led by the Tutsi
minorities and the rebels of the majority Hutus has claimed the
lives of around 200,000 people, most of them civilians, and
displaced 1.2 million others since 1993. Large number of refugees
fled into neighboring Tanzania to seek asylum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
