<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- It is still not clear whether Israel could reach a
peace agreement with the Palestinians during the coming several
months, Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak told his cabinet on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
There have been neither positive responses nor signals from the
Palestinian side and it is still uncertain whether the Israeli-
Palestinian peace talks could be moved forward or the two sides
could strike a deal in a very short period of time, Barak said.
</P>
<P>
However, Barak did not say what measures he will take to push
the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks forward. (Israel-Barak-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- Britain is sending an extra 600 troops to Kosovo to
boost the NATO contingent in the Yugoslav province to help secure
the upcoming Yugoslav presidential and parliamentary elections,
the Times newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The action was taken amid fears that the elections, scheduled
for next Sunday, could lead to new unrest in the Balkans, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The troops will stay in Kosovo for two months in case anything
unexpected should happen during the election period, during which
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic will run for a second four-
year term. (Britain-Kovoso-Troops)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- More deaths have been reported in Russia's breakaway
republic of Chechnya in the last three days, as clashes rise
throughout the war-torn region, Russian media reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported that in Staryie Atagi, a
Chechen town of about 15,000 people, unknown men wearing uniforms
and masks dragged a local resident, Magomed Chikuyev, 34, out of
his house and shot him dead Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Five other civilians, aged between 15 and 70, were killed by
rebels in various parts of the town at dawn on Saturday. The
reasons behind these murders are still unknown, local police said.
(Chechnya-Clashes)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- The Philippine government said Monday that it will no
longer be possible to order a cease-fire and negotiate with the
Abu Sayyaf as military operations against the extremist group
entered the third day.
</P>
<P>
