<HEADLINE> Heyns Wins Bronze Medal in Women's Olympic 100m Breaststroke </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Breaststroke queen Penny
Heyns Monday lost her 100-meter Olympic crown as she finished
third behind teenagers Megan Quann of the United States and
Australia's Leisel Jones to claim South Africa's first medal in
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
Quann clocked 1:07.05secs, Jones 1:07.49 and Heyns 1:07.55.
Heyns led over the first 50m, but the South African duet failed
to hold off the charging Quann and Jones.
</P>
<P>
"Honestly, I'm glad it's over," Heyns said after the medal
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"It hasn't been an easy Olympics. For some reason, it hasn't
been in my legs this season. I had the first 50m, but I was gone
after that. The Olympic Games is difficult," Heyns added. "No
matter how good you are, the pressure here is something else."
</P>
<P>
Heyns, who had a brilliant run last year when she broke 11
world records in the space of two months, went off the boil after
taking a month off following the death of a close friend in Canada
early this year.
</P>
<P>
"I'm just not sure what happened this season. It's been a tough
season and one day I will discuss more about that," she said.
</P>
<P>
But she further said she was satisfied with her bronze medal.
</P>
<P>
"I was a bit emotional out there (during the ceremony), but
that was more to do with that I'm coming to the end of my career."
</P>
<P>
Heyns will get to defend her 200m title later this week,
although she is not prepared to predict.
</P>
<P>
"We'll see what happens," she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
