<HEADLINE> Manila Continues Military Operations Against Abu Sayyaf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine government troops
numbering some 4,000 continued to hunt Monday for the Abu Sayyaf
terrorists in the Sulu towns of Patikul and Talipao where the
group is believed to be holding 19 local and foreign hostages.
</P>
<P>
Generoso Senga, spokesman of the Armed Forces of the
Philippines(AFP), said Monday afternoon in the southern Zamboanga
City that local leaders have expressed their support for the
decision to rescue the hostages through the ongoing military
operations.
</P>
<P>
According to Senga, AFP Chief of Staff Angelo Reyes met with
the officers and members of the Sulu Provincial Peace and Order
CounciL(PPOC) on Monday in the provincial capital of Jolo and
discussed with them the ongoing operations.
</P>
<P>
Senga said the PPOC passed three resolutions on support for
President Joseph Estrada's military option, for the immediate
lifting of the maritime and communication service embargo between
Zamboanga City and Jolo and for the government to set up a human
rights office in Jolo.
</P>
<P>
AFP Chief of Staff Reyes said the military will allow only
inter-island cargo vessels to resume operations starting Tuesday,
but the resumption of passenger service and the reconnection of
communication lines still have to be studied.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman Senga described the situation in Jolo as "generally
peaceful." He quoted mayors of the various towns in Sulu Province
as saying that except for Patikul and Talipao, the other towns are
not affected by the fighting.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Senga denied reports that Caucasian soldiers,
especially American personnel, are in Jolo taking part in the
pursuit operations.
</P>
<P>
He also said that there are no additional casualties, whether
killed or wounded, since the last figures were released to the
media Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The government said Sunday that since military operations began
at 1 a.m. Saturday, six Abu Sayyaf rebels were killed and 20
suspected Abu Sayyaf members captured while four government
soldiers were wounded.
</P>
<P>
Senga dismissed speculations that Abu Sayyaf elements are able
to escape through the dragnets and blockades, saying a maximum
deployment of military resources has been put in place to prevent
that from happening.
</P>
<P>
He said Brigadier General Narciso Abaya, who is the overall
commander of the anti-Abu Sayyaf operations, told General Reyes
that he expects to finish the mission within the week. 
</P>
