<HEADLINE> Singapore's External Trade Up 26.1 Percent in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Singapore's external trade
totaled 42.92 billion Singapore dollars (23.81 billion U.S.
dollars) in August this year, expanding by 26.1 percent over a
year ago, Singapore Trade Development Board (TDB) said Monday in
its monthly bulletin.
</P>
<P>
TDB attributed the robust growth to buoyant demand for key
electronic products, as well as sustained demand from key Asian
economies.
</P>
<P>
In August, non-oil domestic export expanded by 17.7 percent,
driven by continued strong growth in domestic exports of
integrated circuits, telecommunications equipment, ink cartridges
and non-electronic products.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil re-exports grew by 34.5 percent during the month,
reflecting strong growth in all major markets and products.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil imports, excluding aircraft and ships, continued to
expand at a healthy rate of 25.9 percent in August, largely on the
back of the growth of electronic products such as integrated
circuits, telecommunication equipment, capacitors and CD-ROM
drives.
</P>
<P>
Non-oil domestic export to Malaysia, Japan and Hong Kong
expanded further in August by 28.3, 23.1 and 30.2 percent
respectively while that to the United States and the European
Union edged up marginally by 4.8 and 0.4 percent separately.
</P>
</TEXT>
