<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Takes Measures to Improve Children's Health </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Identifying polio and diarrhea
as the main culprits for the high child mortality rate in the
country, the Bangladeshi health minister Sunday said the
government has taken up massive programs for the development of
child health.
</P>
<P>
"Eradication of polio and control of diarrhea can help reduce
the child mortality rate to a great extent," Health Minister
Sheikh Fazlul Karim Selim said while inaugurating a national
workshop on child health development in Cox's Bazaar, a southeast
coastal district in the country, according to an official press
release here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Although the present government has succeeded in its efforts to
reduce the child mortality rate, the rate is still much higher
compared with other countries, the minister admitted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the government's acute respiratory infection
program, Selim said it has contributed a lot to reducing the
country's child mortality rate.
</P>
<P>
Under this program, he said, almost all doctors of the country'
s 64 districts have been given training. All health workers are
expected to complete their training by November 2000, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that in Bangladesh the under-five child
mortality rate is 9.2 percent, infant mortality rate 5.7 percent
and maternal mortality rate 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the government would observe the coming National
Immunization Week in a befitting manner with a view to eradicating
polio from Bangladesh by 2000 although the World Health
Organization (WHO) says Bangladesh needs another year to reach the
goal.
</P>
<P>
Selim also emphasized the need for providing education to
school students on malnutrition, blindness caused by Vitamin A and
iodine deficiencies, breast-feeding and diarrhea control measures
under the health education program.
</P>
<P>
Attending the workshop were all civil surgeons of the country'
s 64 districts, divisional health directors and country
representatives of the U.N. Children's Fund and the WHO. 
</P>
</TEXT>
