<HEADLINE> Manila Rules Out Cease-fire With Abu Sayyaf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government said
Monday that it will no longer be possible to order a cease-fire
and negotiate with the Abu Sayyaf as military operations against
the extremist group entered the third day.
</P>
<P>
"At this point, it is not likely that there will be a cease-
fire or that negotiations with the Abu Sayyaf will resume for the
release of the hostages," Press Secretary and Presidential
Spokesman Ricardo Puno said in his regular press briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said it would be difficult to order a cease-fire at this
stage when soldiers are already in the field and military
operations are ongoing. "I think events have overtaken us."
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada ordered a pre-dawn military
attack last Saturday against the Abu Sayyaf rebels who are now
holding one American, two French journalists, three Malaysians and
13 Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
The group has reportedly amassed millions of dollars in ransom
for the release of 20 of the 21 mostly foreign hostages they
seized from Malaysia's resort island of Sipadan on April 23. While
freeing some of their captives, they took new hostages for ransom.
</P>
<P>
Puno also reiterated the operation guidelines ordered by the
president to the Armed Forces of the Philippines and the
Philippine National Police, the paramount of which is to exhaust
all means to safely rescue the 19 hostages still in the hands of
the Abu Sayyaf.
</P>
<P>
Other guidelines, according to Puno, are quick resolution of
the situation, an immediate stop to the lawlessness in the area
and deterring of other groups from doing similar terroristic acts.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Puno said President Estrada has sought the
understanding of the whole world on the actions taken by the
government against the Abu Sayyaf in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
On criticisms coming from the French government of the military
operations, Puno said the president is asking for their
understanding and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also said that through the Department of Foreign Affairs,
the president has made it very clear to foreign governments what
he considers to be of national interest on this particular issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
