<HEADLINE> Broadband Users Double to 250,000 in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The number of broadband
users in Singapore has more than doubled over the last six months
to 250,000, the InfoComm Development Authority of Singapore (IDA)
announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
Encouraged by this trend, IDA said it is launching an
international content hosting scheme which aims to enhance
Singapore's position as a broadband content hub in the region.
</P>
<P>
Lim Swee Say, minister of state for the Ministry of
Communications and Information Technology, said Monday at an IDA
seminar that the duration of support under the scheme will be
lengthened to two years, compared with six months under the
existing Online Hosting Scheme.
</P>
<P>
Describing the outlook for broadband in Singapore as exciting,
Lim outlined the focus for the country going forward.
</P>
<P>
"We have three key priorities in the coming years. First is to
speed up the pace of innovation in broadband applications; second,
to broaden the base of broadband penetration; and third, to foster
greater collaboration in the Asia-Pacific region," Lim said.
</P>
<P>
During the seminar, IDA also signed memoranda of understanding
with seven strategic industry partners, including Microsoft and
content providers from Japan, South Korea, India and China's Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
They will help build up a critical mass of broadband content
providers in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Another new initiative introduced is the setting up of an
industry-led broadband media association to help spur strategic
alliances and business networking. 
</P>
</TEXT>
