<HEADLINE> Philippine Peso Ends Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine peso ended
weaker against the U.S. dollar Monday in line with the falling
regional currencies.
</P>
<P>
The peso closed 45.82 against the green back, weaker than the
previous close of 45.59 last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the peso tracked the downward direction of the
Thai baht and Indonesian rupiah.
</P>
<P>
"We're just aligning with the prices of other regional
currencies.The baht and the rupiah dropped sharply over the
weekend. So this is just initial market jitters from weaker
regional currencies," a dealer at a U.S. bank said.
</P>
<P>
Dealers added that the market has largely discounted the
political strife in the south including the military's attack that
began Saturday against the extremist Abu Sayyaf group which is
holding 19 foreign and Filipino hostages.
</P>
<P>
"A positive reaction from the market may only be expected if
the government finally wins the war against the Abu Sayyaf," a
dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Value turnover reached an average 50.9 million dollars
throughout the day's session. 
