<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Deaths Reported As New Clashes Rise in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 18 (Xinhua) -- More deaths have been reported
in Russia's breakaway republic of Chechnya in the last three days,
as clashes rise throughout the war-torn region, Russian media
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency reported that in Staryie Atagi, a
Chechen town of about 15,000 people, unknown men wearing uniforms
and masks dragged a local resident, Magomed Chikuyev, 34, out of
his house and shot him dead Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
Five other civilians, aged between 15 and 70, were killed by
rebels in various parts of the town at dawn on Saturday. The
reasons behind these murders are still unknown, local police said.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, Alexei Dershelenya, ataman of the Kizlyar Cossack
District of Dagestan, together with an aide to the district
military commandant and a Russian army sergeant, were killed by
automatic weapons fire while traveling by car to the outskirts of
the village of Kargalinskaya, located in the Shelkovsky region of
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
In another incident, deputy head of the police department in
the Chechen district of Vedeno, Col. Shamil Azayev, was killed by
an unidentified assailant at his home Saturday evening after a
curfew was imposed, Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, new clashes and fire exchanges between Russian
troops and Chechen rebel groups are happening with increasing
frequency, deepening fears that the rebels have launched a more
intensive hit-and-run war against the federal units, causing more
casualties on both sides.
</P>
<P>
Russian news agencies Sunday said that federal forces killed
six rebels and detained another while a group of militants
attempted to break through federal checkpoints outside the village
of Chechen-Aul towards the south village of Stariye Atagi.
</P>
<P>
Ammunition, including charges for an armored vehicle, was
confiscated after the fighting, the Russian military said.
</P>
<P>
Six other rebels were killed and four Arab mercenaries were
captured in Chechnya's Vedeno district Sunday during a special
federal operation, the Russian staff in the North Caucasus said.
</P>
<P>
Russian Mi-24 gunships also destroyed three rebel bases
identified by ground reconnaissance groups on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Su-25 attack planes flew eight combat missions and destroyed
rebel positions in Vedeno and Nozhai-Yurt districts, while Mi-24
and Mi-8 helicopters flew nearly 30 missions, destroying five
enemy strongholds and two arms depots.
</P>
<P>
Over the past 24 hours, federal sappers averted two terrorist
attacks on office buildings. Meanwhile, checkpoints came under
rebel fire seven times. Police disposed of a powerful explosive
device set to go off in a marketplace in Chernorechye, a suburb of
Grozny, the staff said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The police said they also prevented a number of terrorist
attacks in other parts of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Rebels are avoiding head-on confrontation with the federal
troops, ambushing Russian units instead and then retreating in
orderly fashion, often with support of local populations,
according to the Russian military.
</P>
<P>
The military also reported that almost all temporary police
stations in the capital city of Grozny were attacked by Chechen
guerrillas on Saturday, but there were no losses of servicemen.
</P>
<P>
Rebel firings upon Russian police stations and block-posts
have lately become more frequent, and Saturday's incidents were no
more special than what happens everyday, Russian military official
in Grozny admitted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
