<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Recovery on Track But Still Fragile: World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's economic recovery
is on track but remains fragile, the World Bank said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Thai economy has continued to expand in 2000 while exports
remain the main driver of growth, the bank said in a report on
East Asia, expecting Thailand to grow by 4 to 5 percent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
However, "the increased market volatility, the increase in oil
prices and the uncertainty arising from forthcoming elections may
have adversely affected consumer confidence," it pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"The pace and quality of the financial and corporate reform
continue to be the major constraint to the full cementing of the
recovery," it said.
</P>
<P>
Non-performing loans still represent 32 percent of total credit,
which could jeopardize the financing of new investments in sectors
that are currently running close to full capacity, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
A major downside risk to the growth scenario is the observed
slowdown in manufacturing production which reflects weak domestic
demand while the dependence of the recovery on foreign demand
creates another important risk, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, while market volatility has increased, it is "unlikely
" to lead to turmoil, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's external position remains comfortable and its fiscal
policy continues to support the recovery. While public debt of the
country has increased and will pose challenges in the future, it
is manageable.
</P>
<P>
Monetary policy continues to be accommodating and total factor
productivity and the quality of the labor force are trending-up.
</P>
<P>
Possibly because the market was discontent with Thailand's pace
of reforms and political uncertainty, the Stock Exchange of
Thailand index has lost 36 percent of its value since January 2000
and the baht has depreciated by 7.7 percent to below 41 against
the U.S. dollar, it said.
</P>
<P>
However, the bank pointed out that these adjustments "do not
point towards a new crisis as the balance of payments situation
remains comfortable." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
