<HEADLINE> Britain Sends More Troops to Kosovo to Secure Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Britain is sending an extra
600 troops to Kosovo to boost the NATO contingent in the Yugoslav
province to help secure the upcoming Yugoslav presidential and
parliamentary elections, the Times newspaper reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The action was taken amid fears that the elections, scheduled
for next Sunday, could lead to new unrest in the Balkans, the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The troops will stay in Kosovo for two months in case anything
unexpected should happen during the election period, during which
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic will run for a second four-
year term.
</P>
<P>
The extra British troops from the Second Battalion Light
Infantry will be joined over the next few weeks by three other
infantry battalions, from France, Italy and Greece, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
The NATO forces in Kosovo, which were deployed in the province
after last year's air campaign, is expected to increase by more
than 2,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Belgrade is holding a show trial against Western
leaders for the war crimes they committed, including British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, U.S. President Bill Clinton and 12 other
Western leaders.
</P>
<P>
Belgrade's Palace of Justice is holding a trial for those
regarded as the most responsible for NATO's 78-day air campaign
which killed more than 800 people, including about 500 civilians,
and destroyed much of Yugoslavia's infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
The defendants are accused of using such illegal weapons as
cluster bombs and causing criminal damage such as polluting the
River Danube and attempting to murder Milosevic, the report added.
</P>
</TEXT>
