<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inflation Down in EU, Euro Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Inflation went down in both
the European Union (EU) and the euro zone in August, Eurostat
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Luxembourg-based statistical agency of the European Union
said that inflation fell from 2.2 percent in July to 2.0 percent
in August in the 15-nation EU. It dropped from 2.4 percent in
July to 2.3 percent in August in the 11-nation single currency
area.
</P>
<P>
Yet just one year ago, the inflation rate for the European
Union and the euro zone were both at 1.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has set a ceiling for the 2.0 percent
inflation rate and the European Central Bank has been raising its
benchmark lending interest rate so as to curb the rising inflation.
</P>
<P>
In August, the lowest inflation among the 15 EU member states
was found in Britain, where the inflation was at 0.6 percent. The
highest inflation was registered in Ireland at 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
However, only five of the 15 EU member states had below-2.0
percent inflation in the month reported on by the Eurostat,
signaling bad news for the plummeting single currency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
