on their planned music joint venture, the European Commission said
on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A meeting was held on Monday between European Union Competition
Commissioner Mario Monti and senior executives from the two
entertainment giants.
</P>
<P>
"The meeting took place in the morning," said Monti's
spokesperson Amelia Torres. "The merging parties made proposals
which they have yet to formalize."
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the executive body of the 15-nation
European Union, needs to examine the proposals made by EMI and
Warner Music and to test them on the market, according to the
spokesperson.
</P>
<P>
It was expected that the European Commission would be able to
consult with other entertainment businesses to see whether the
concessions are enough.
</P>
<P>
EMI and Warner Music had until midnight Tuesday to offer their
concessions concerning the merger review by the commission. The
two companies said late last week that it was still hopeful that
the European Commission will allow their joint venture to go ahead.
</P>
<P>
The commission is expected to give its verdict on the 20
billion U.S. dollar music joint venture on October 18. 
