<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mobile Phone Users to Outnumber Those of Conventional Phone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Wireless voice subscribers will
exceed wired, conventional telephone subscribers by the end of
2002, a leading scientist for the Motorola Company said today.
</P>
<P>
"Even more surprising is the fact that wireless Internet
subscribers will surpass wired (by computer) Internet subscribers
by the same date," said Dennis Roberson, a senior scientist for
Motorola.
</P>
<P>
Roberson made the remarks at the annual meeting of the China
Association for Science and Technology (CAST), China's largest
academic meeting in Xi'an, capital of northwest China's Shaanxi
Province.
</P>
<P>
In a report delivered at the meeting, Dennis Roberson said
that while the incredibly rapid growth of the Internet is
generally understood, it is less well known than the wireless
telephone and in particular wireless Internet capability that are
also growing at unprecedented rates.
</P>
<P>
He said his prediction is based on the fact that in the near
future, most cellular phones will have Internet access capability.
</P>
<P>
"To fully realize the potential of wireless Internet access
requires three factors," said Roberson, "a wireless data rate
which roughly matches current wired Internet data rates, an
aggregate wireless capacity which roughly matches current wired
Internet capacity, and a novel user interface which allows for
limitations and advantages of a handled device."
</P>
<P>
Roberson said that Motorola is currently experimenting with a
full range of multimedia data types including video, image, data,
music and voice technologies which will create entirely new forms
of human interaction.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that by the end of June, China had 120 million
wired telephone subscribers and 60 million mobile phone users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
