<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq May Replace U.S. Dollar in Business Dealings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Resisting the United States
both politically and militarily over the past 10 years, Iraq is now
trying to show its defiance over the U.S. domination in the world
economy.
</P>
<P>
At present, a group of financial experts, appointed by the Iraqi
government, are studying the possibility of replacing the U.S.
dollar with another "politically correct" currency as termed by the
Iraqi officials.
</P>
<P>
Their study will mainly focus on the euro, officially launched
on January 1, 1999 by the European Union (EU) as a counter-balance
to the U.S. dollar in the world financial market as well as in the
world economy.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government made the decision during a cabinet meeting
last week, claiming that the dollar is manipulated by the Zionism
(Israeli) and American interests.
</P>
<P>
However, it seems that the Iraqi leadership has made a rather
dubious choice, given the fact that the euro has fallen steadily
against the dollar since its inception.
</P>
<P>
The euro has been relatively weak in recent months. The latest
exchange rate between the euro and the dollar stood at 1:0.86, some
30 percent depreciation compared with the glorious figure of 1:1.18
when the EU single currency was born.
</P>
<P>
Despite the decision by the Iraqi government to dump the dollar,
the greenback remains the sole foreign currency of choice in Iraq,
as the Iraqi dinar has fluctuated wildly against the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Ordinary Iraqis appeared not optimistic about the prospect of
replacing the dollar.
</P>
<P>
"This act represents our complete rejection of America. We want
nothing to do with America, but we have no choice but to deal with
the dollar," a money exchange shop owner who did not disclose his
name said.
</P>
<P>
"What can we do?" a man who called himself Mohammad said, "Iraq
can make little choice as its economy is now under the control of
the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
Under U.N. resolutions, all the revenues for Iraq's oil exports
flow into the U.N. escrow bank in Paris and Iraq can get no direct
money from selling its oil.
</P>
<P>
Ever since the Arab Baath Socialist Party came into power in
Iraq in 1968, Iraq's foreign reserves and overseas transactions
have all been in U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
