<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Long-Term Returns Seen From Indian New Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- With the rapid development
of information technology (IT), investors in India's new economy
stocks have reaped a big harvest in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said returns on the new economy stocks were phenomenal,
ranging from 400 percent to 2,000 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
A person who purchased 100 shares of Infosys, the country's
software giant, on August 31, 1995, at 477 rupees with a face
value of 10 rupees would be holding 800 shares with a face value
of 5 rupees but a market rate of 8,373.15 rupees on August 31,
2000.
</P>
<P>
This means that an investment of 47,700 rupees fetched 6,698,
520 rupees for an investor. Thus an investor made a total
appreciation of 11,943 percent in five years with average annual
appreciation being 2,788.6 percent. Other IT stocks also did well
with Satyam Computers, Wipro and SSI following close behind.
</P>
<P>
The reasons for such appreciation are obvious. Infosys's gross
revenues increased from 930 million rupees in the year ended March
1996 to 9.2146 billion rupees in the year ended March 2000, a
growth of nearly 10 times in just five years.
</P>
<P>
Its net profits increased faster from 210.1 million rupees in
March 1996 to 2.8595 billion rupees in March 2000. The company
also issued two bonuses and a stock split in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
In the five years, Infosys' stocks always did well but the
major leap came after it got listed at Nasdaq, the exchange for
technology companies in the United States in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
Other major IT companies also did well with Satyam Computers'
revenue rising from 537.6 million rupees in the year ended March
1996 to 6.7901 billion rupees in the year ended March 2000.
Profits growth kept pace, moving from 135.7 million rupees to 1.
3486 billion rupees in the five years.
</P>
<P>
However, not all IT companies did well. The stock price of
Onward Technologies moved nowhere in the past five years because
the company did badly. Only in the past year, it started to get
its act together.
</P>
<P>
Analysts warned that investors in tech stocks at current levels
should not expect the spectacular returns made in the past years
to continue and that returns are going to be just reasonable.
</P>
<P>
Also, they said, people who bought tech stocks in February 2000
are still licking their wounds because the markets have crashed
considerably. Companies, which have failed to meet the
expectations have been battered mercilessly.
</P>
<P>
However, they predicted that stocks of the tech sector should
continue to do well with a growth rate of over 500 percent for the
next few years and investors can hope for decent returns. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
