<HEADLINE> 158,000 Disabled Pupils Enrolled in Ugandan Schools </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- About 158,000 disabled pupils
in Uganda have been enrolled under the Universal Primary Education
(UPE) program, a senior official told Xinhua in a telephone
interview on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the UPE program, everyone will have access to free
education including the disabled children, said Uganda Minister
for Primary Education Mrs.Geradine Bitamazire.
</P>
<P>
"The Ministry of Education and Sports is working out a policy
to see that affirmative action on people with disability is put in
place," she said.
</P>
<P>
"We have a lot companies from some groups of people who want a
national special school syllabus formulated for people with
disability and we shall meet in dialogue to cover that issue," she
added.
</P>
<P>
Universal Primary Education is the provision of Basic Education
to all Ugandan children of school-going age. The main goal is to
enable Ugandan children of school-going age (6-12) to receive
quality education and remain in school and complete the Primary
Cycle of Education. 
</P>
