<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuel Scarcity Bites Nigeria Harder  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The worsening fuel scarcity is
spreading from Nigeria's commercial capital Lagos to all the major
cities of the country at the weekend while oil prices in the black
market keep increasing, local media reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The "no fuel" sign was displayed at most filling stations and
rowdy scenes were spotted in a few stations still selling fuel
with endless queues of vehicles waiting for petrol.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, black market transactions with touts hawking the
scarce petrol in cans at exorbitant prices.
</P>
<P>
In Lagos, the price of petrol in black market is hitting 450-
500 naira (about four to five U.S. dollar) for four liters while
the official price is 22 naira per liter.
</P>
<P>
In the neighboring states of Ogun, Ondo and Oyo, prices had
shot up to the same levels while in Benin, capital of Edo State,
four liters of petrol reached the roof of 700-800 naira.
</P>
<P>
The rowdy scenes at filling stations across the country have
brought back memories of the late Sani Abacha's era when Nigerians
suffered fuel scarcity almost perpetually.
</P>
<P>
With the strike from last week by the two industrial unions in
the fuel supply sector continuing to date, Nigerians have come
again under the excruciating pain of fuel scarcity and the
consequent agony of a people with so many vehicles but no petrol
to power them.
</P>
<P>
The situation would be even worse as the protesting oil workers,
Petroleum and Natural Gas Senior Staff Association of Nigeria and
the National Union of Petroleum and Natural Gas Workers, vowed
Sunday night that they would continue with the strike action until
their demands are met. 
</P>
</TEXT>
