<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Produce More Crude Oil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 18 (Xinhua) Nigeria has been allocated an
extra 65,600 barrels of crude oil per day by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), local media reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The increment of the oil production quota, effective from
October 1, was decided at OPEC's recent 111th Extra-Ordinary
Summit in Vienna, Austria. Nigeria takes a share of 65,600 bpd of
the agreed 800,000 increased production quota among the
organization's 11 member states.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, the biggest oil-producing country in Africa with a
daily output of over two million barrels, lists the sixth among
the world's leading oil-exporting nations.
</P>
<P>
A senior Nigerian official from the office of the Special
Adviser on Petroleum and Energy Matters, who attended the Vienna
Summit, was quoted as saying that the increment of oil production
quota was aimed to stabilize the rising price in the international
oil market.
</P>
<P>
There was a growing fear inside the OPEC that the world economy
might face a depression if the rising oil price is unchecked and
there would be an increase in the prices of other commodities at
the world market, hence causing damages both to oil consumers and
producers.
</P>
<P>
The oil price hit 36 U.S. dollars per barrel in the world
market just as the OPEC ended the summit when they failed to reach
agreement to bring down the price to about 30 dollars per barrel
after heated discussions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
