<HEADLINE> Interview: Integration of Disciplines Critical for Medical Development (Part Two) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
......a coherent picture," he said.
</P>
<P>
The accepted definition of biomedical engineering that it is
the application of engineering principles and methodologies to the
solution of biological and medical problems is much too narrow
today, Jaron said.
</P>
<P>
He gave the current definition as "Bioengineering integrates
physical, chemical, or mathematical sciences and engineering
principles for the study of biology, medicine, behavior, or health.
It advances fundamental concepts, create knowledge from the
molecular to the organ systems level."
</P>
<P>
Jaron is a member of a delegation comprising 20 leading
biomedical engineering express from the United States, the United
Kingdom and France, who kicked off their academic visit to China
Monday with a workshop held Monday in the Chinese University of
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of this delegation is to promote and improve
communication of biomedical engineering activities in universities,
professional organizations, and health care industries between
China and the countries represented in the delegation.
</P>
<P>
The 13-day visit, which will take the delegation later to
several Chinese mainland cities including Beijing, Xi'an and
Shanghai, is arranged by the People to People Ambassador Programs,
founded in 1956 by then U.S. President Dwight Eisenhower to
promote friendly relations among all the countries through the
medium of scientific, professional and technical exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
