<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0149 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Interview: Integration of Disciplines Critical for Medical Development (Part One) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Dov Jaron, president of the
International Federation for Medical and Biological Engineering,
emphasized on the importance of the integration of medicine,
biology, physics, mathematics and biomedical engineering during an
interview to Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He predicted the health care will see dramatic progress in the
new century because of new technologies.
</P>
<P>
"New drugs will be developed through rational design procedures
rather than by trial and error as it is done today. They will be
tailored to individual needs," he said
</P>
<P>
"Diagnosis will depend on deep and full understanding as to how
genes, molecules, cells, organs and the whole organism function as
a holistic system. And finally, preventive methods and therapeutic
procedures will target the molecular origin of the disease."
</P>
<P>
Jaron said, to achieve these dramatic changes, people need to
expand the base of biomedical research and develop true
interdisciplinary team approaches to problem solving.
</P>
<P>
"But even more important, in my opinion -- medical and
biological scientists will need to establish ever close
collaboration with physical scientists, mathematicians and
biomedical engineers," he said.
</P>
<P>
Biomedical scientists are best at reductionism, which strives
to break up the living system to its most elementary constituents
and understand the structure and function of the smallest elements
of the organism, of the fundamental components of cells and
molecules, according to Jaron.
</P>
<P>
But it often ignores the effects of interconnections between
the individual elements, because the overall properties are often
different than the sum of their parts.
</P>
<P>
This disadvantage can be made up for by engineers, who excel at
integration.
</P>
<P>
"Engineers possess the analytical and quantitative tools that
make it possible to synthesize and understand how the different
system components interact and how the emergent properties of
complex systems are formed. Engineers are also adept at
consolidating large amount of data into a coherent picture," he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing to Hold Sino-German Environment Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Sino-German 2000 Environment
Cooperation Conference will be held in mid-December, announced the
State Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA) today.
</P>
<P>
The conference, which is an important meeting initiated by the
Chinese premier and German chancellor, will be a new start for
comprehensive cooperation in the area of environmental protection
between the two countries in the 21st century, said Xie Zhenhua,
minister of the SEPA today.
</P>
<P>
He said that SEPA will cooperate with other Chinese government
organizations and some German government organizations to prepare
for the conference.
</P>
<P>
The conference will help expand the level of cooperation
between China and Germany, and promote their working relationship
when it comes to protecting the environment. It will also provide
an opportunity for China to introduce advanced management
experience and concepts from Germany, in order for the two
countries to work together to play a more active role in
protecting the environment on an international scale.
</P>
<P>
More than 500 Chinese and German representatives will attend
the conference, December 12-13, in Beijing. They will discuss
topics of utilization and protection of natural resources,
pollution control and prevention and city planning and management.
</P>
</TEXT>
