<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Urged to Disarm East Timorese Militia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Visiting United States
Defense Secretary William Cohen here Monday urged the Indonesian
government to be serious in dealing with East Timorese militia,
saying the failure to do so would jeopardize its relations with
the international community.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also reiterated the U.S. government commitments to
support Indonesia in building democracy.
</P>
<P>
"I have just finished meetings with President Wahid, Vice
President Megawati, Coordinating Minister for Political, Social
and Security Affairs Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono, Defense Minister
Mahfud, and Admiral Widodo, Commander of the National Security
forces (TNI)," Cohen told a press conference at the Halim
Perdanakusumah military airport, before leaving for Thailand.
</P>
<P>
"In every meeting I made the same points: The United States
strongly supports Indonesia's historic transition to democracy,
but the transition must include a clear commitment to the rule of
law and an end to the violence in East and West Timor," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cohen also reiterated the U.S. government's
condemnation against the armed attack in Atambua, suspected to has
been launched by East Timorese militia group on September 6, which
killed international workers.
</P>
<P>
"The United States and the entire international community have
condemned this brutal attack by militia killers and have called on
the Indonesian authorities to take immediate action to deal with
the Timor crisis," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
"Fail to do so will have consequences for Jakarta's relations
with the international community and could jeopardize continued
economic assistance to Indonesia," he warned.
</P>
<P>
He also said that "the (U.N.) Security Council still intends to
send a mission to Jakarta and Atambua to discuss Indonesia's
implementation of the (U.N.) resolution."
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has passed a resolution 1319, which insists
that Indonesia disarm and disband all militia elements, ensure the
safety and welfare of all refugees and humanitarian aid workers,
and arrest and prosecute those responsible for the Atambua's
incident.
</P>
<P>
"President Wahid and the leadership of the TNI have given their
assurances that Indonesia is prepared to move quickly and
decisively to deal with the West Timor crisis," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
Cohen also implicitly warned Indonesia over possible
international sanction if the country failed in response the U.S.
government's calls.
</P>
<P>
Cohen, who arrived here Sunday evening for a two-day visit,
said that the U.S. government also welcomed the Indonesian
government's move in dealing with human right abuser in East Timor
as well as other areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the United States keeps supporting the
ongoing reforms program in Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
"The United States and every country in the region wants these
reforms to succeed, so that Indonesia will be a country where the
people can live up to their potential, rather than be dragged down
by their problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But some forces in Indonesia seek to undermine these reforms
through violence and terror, such as the cowards who bombed the
Jakarta Stock Exchange last week. These destructive forces must
not succeed," the secretary said.
</P>
<P>
In connection with the TNI's future, Cohen said the United
States wants to see it to be more professional, saying that "
Indonesia needs a strong, professional military under civilian
control, and the United States is eager to help the TNI become a
professional force that respects human rights and is respected for
its military might."
</P>
<P>
During his Asia's tour, Cohen, who earlier visited the
Philippines, will go from Indonesia to Thailand, South Korea and
Japan. He is due to return to Washington on September 22. 
</P>
</TEXT>
