<HEADLINE> One Kenyan Runner Left out in 400m Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Although Kenya's 400m runner
Simon Kemboi arrived in Australia for the Olympic Games in August,
but on Monday he still did not know whether he would be accepted
in the starters' list because his name was left out.
</P>
<P>
Kenya Amateur Athletic Association (KAAA) submitted three names
for the event, but only two entered in the starting list.
</P>
<P>
KAAA coaches are worried that Kemboi maybe would lose the
chance to compete, but the team's chef de mission, Jackson Tuwei,
said that they would persuade the Games organizers to include
Kemboi in the starting line scheduled for September 22 heats.
</P>
<P>
Tuwei said Games officials in Sydney were not convinced that
Kemboi had attained the qualifying time to run in Olympics.
</P>
<P>
He said the KAAA had inadvertently sent to organizers the wrong
times, but on realizing this, the organization corrected the error
by sending updated information.
</P>
<P>
But one coach said that issue was far more complicated than the
Kenya management committee cares to admit.
</P>
<P>
The coach said that Kemboi's qualifying time was attained
during the Kenya's trials but the International Olympic Committee
officials did not recommend the timing devices used and could,
therefore, not ratify Kemboi's qualifying time.
</P>
<P>
But Tuwei said they had taken up the matter with International
Amateur Athletic Federation which endorsed Kemboi's result and it
is only a matter of time before Games officials in Sydney are
updated with the new development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
