<HEADLINE> Malchow Carries Top Form for Men's Butterfly Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Tom Malchow of the United
States will be the favorite heading in the final fo the men's 200m
butterfly on Tuesday night after winning his semifinal in a new
Olympic record time of 1:56.02.
</P>
<P>
The lead changed several times in the race and Malchow, who
also broke the Olympic record in his heat swim, waited until the
last 50m to move ahead of the field.
</P>
<P>
He was challenged in the last few meters by Russian Anatoli
Poliakov, who finished in 1:56.78 and is the second fastest
qualifier for the final.
</P>
<P>
Also finishing strongly were 15-year-old American Michael
Phelps in 1:57.00 and Atlanta 200m butterfly finalist Franck
Esposito of France who clocked a 1:57.04
</P>
<P>
Denys Sylant'yev of Ukraine followed up on his solid heat swim
by winning his semifinal in 1:56.81. He was pushed all the way by
Britain's Stephen Parry, who finished third in 1:57.23. Justin
Norris of Australia accelerated in the last few meters to finish
just behind Sylant'yev in 1:57.10.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion Denis Pankratov scraped into the final with a
time of 1:57.24 and will swim in lane eight. 
</P>
