<HEADLINE> HK Stocks Fall Over 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong stocks plunged
more than 4 percent Monday to the lowest level in the past three
month, affected by the high oil price and the weak Wall Street
performance last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index slumped 689.37 points, or 4.24 percent, to
close at 15,560.16, well below its 250-day moving average of 15,
809.94.
</P>
<P>
The turnover amounted to 11.514 billion HK dollars (1.476
billion U.S. dollars), up 1.124 billion HK dollars (144 million U.
S. dollars) from last Friday.
</P>
<P>
HSBC Holdings, which fell 4.5 percent Monday, dragged down the
Hang Seng Index on fears that the weak euro would brought negative
impact on global banking earnings.
</P>
<P>
Of the four sub-indices, only Utilities edged up 0.15 percent,
while Finance, Properties and Commerce &AMP; Industry sharply
decreased 4.27 percent, 4.46 percent and 4.56 percent,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
China-related index also ended lower with the H-shares down 4.
60 percent and the red chips down 4.66 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng IT Index and the Hang Seng IT Portfolio Index
suffered even severely and slumped by 5.38 percent and 5.88
percent.
</P>
<P>
The blue chips were down 238.84 points, or 1.47 percent, to
open at 16,010.69 Monday. The market kept declining and closed the
morning session down at 645.10 points, or 3.97 percent, at 15,604.
43. 
</P>
</TEXT>
