<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish, Greek FMs Add Momentum to Improve Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Turkish and Greek foreign
ministers agreed to work together to discuss and implement a series
of confidence-building measures between the two countries, Turkish
Daily News reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached by Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem
and his Greek counterpart George Papandreou on Sunday on the
sidelines of the United Nations General Assembly in New York.
</P>
<P>
Following their talks, Cem said that Turkey was ready to discuss
Aegean disputes with Greece under the guidelines of international
law, adding that confidence-building measures would cover the
Aegean issues.
</P>
<P>
Turkey insists that the boundaries of either countries'
territorial waters and air space in the Aegean Sea be solved by
bilateral dialogue while Greece maintains that the only dispute in
the Aegean is that of continental shelf rights and wants the
International Court of Justice in the Hague to arbitrate.
</P>
<P>
The two North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) members almost
went to war in 1996 over claims to rocky islets in the Aegean
called Imia in Greek and Kardak in Turkish. Tension was defused
only after mediation by the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus issue also remains as a major sticking point in
promoting relations between Ankara and Athens.
</P>
<P>
The Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974 when Turkey
occupied its northern third in response to an Athens-engineered
coup.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two Aegean rivals have improved
significantly since last year, following a diplomatic rapprochement
and a burst of cooperation in the wake of devastating earthquakes
in both countries.
</P>
<P>
In a further sign of warming relations, Cem and Papandreou
decided to submit a joint bid to host the 2008 European Soccer
Championship, and agreed to organize a youth exchange program
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
They have also decided to meet in October respectively in
Turkish northwestern city Marmaris and Greek Rhodes to discuss
bilateral relations, particularly issues relating to tourism.
</P>
<P>
Analysts viewed these moves as new steps taken by the two
countries to further the rapprochement of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have proposed measures to improve relations,
including reducing the number of military exercises of the two
countries, opening direct lines of communication between their
chiefs of general staff, and the coast guard and military aircraft
flying unarmed over sensitive areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
