<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Civilians Killed in Crossfire in S. Philippine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Four civilians were killed
when they were caught in the crossfire in the fighting between
Philippine government forces and Abu Sayyaf terrorists in Sulu
province, the Office of Civil Defense (OCD) said Monday.
</P>
<P>
This brought to 10 people killed, including six Abu Sayyaf
members, during the three-day military operations. Four soldiers
were earlier wounded in the initial phase of the fighting last
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mlgabal Capistrano, OCD chief, said 913 families evacuated from
their homes to avoid being cornered in the fighting now on its
third day in the southern Sulu province.
</P>
<P>
Government forces backed by planes, helicopters and tanks
continued their ground and air assault on Abu Sayyaf lairs in the
jungles of Patikul, Talipao and Maimbung to rescue 19 hostages,
four of them foreigners, including American Jeffrey Schilling.
</P>
<P>
Capistrano said all the four victims, including an 11-year old
girl, were caught in the crossfire. But he didn't mention when
these people were killed.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has released an initial amount of 900,
000 pesos (20,000 U.S. dollars) for the purchase of foods for the
evacuees who are now housed in 10 evacuation centers in Sulu
province.
</P>
<P>
Government officials said the 19 hostages are still alive but
were brought along by their captors during their retreat.
</P>
<P>
Before the attack, the Abu Sayyaf had threatened to kill the
hostages if the military would rescue the captives.
</P>
<P>
The government has imposed a news blackout to prevent the
telegraphing of military moves, but some officials estimated that
the military will wind up its operation in a week's time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
