<HEADLINE> Some Australians Prevented from Donating Blood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Australians who lived in
Britain during the outbreak of mad cow's disease are to be
prevented from donating blood.
</P>
<P>
Radio ABC reported that the Blood Donation Referral committee
in the country held a phone conference Monday morning to discuss
the latest evidence from a Scottish scientific team which says
there is now preliminary evidence that mad cow's disease can be
spread through blood transfusions.
</P>
<P>
ABC said all state officials have agreed to prevent those lived
in Britain for more than six months between 1980 and 1996 from
donating blood.
</P>
<P>
The final decision is to be made by ministers.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Austria and New Zealand are reported to put
the ban in place. 
</P>
</TEXT>
