<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Revises Upwards Asia's Economic Growth Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank has
revised upwards its forecast for developing Asia's Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) growth this year to 6.9 percent from a previously
projected 6.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The upward revision of the regional growth forecast for 2000 is
based on stronger domestic demand and sustained growth in external
demand, the bank said in its latest regional economic report
released here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The regional economic growth in 2001 is forecast to moderate to
6.5 percent, according to the report, The Asian Development
Outlook 2000 Update, which is a mid-year update of the annual
Asian Development Outlook, published in April.
</P>
<P>
The report says that domestic investment demand, while still
below pre-crisis levels in most of developing Asia, is likely to
strengthen, as excess capacity is utilized and competitive
pressures force production capacity to be upgraded.
</P>
<P>
Improved private consumption demand is expected to offset
slackening public sector demand as governments restore fiscal
balances within the region, it says.
</P>
<P>
External demand is likely to remain buoyant on account of
stronger growth in interregional trade, a consolidation of
recovery in Europe and Japan, and continued, though slower, demand
growth in the United States, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The report notes, however, that growth is uneven among
economies in the region and warns that volatility in the region's
financial markets underscores concerns that need to be addressed
if growth is to be sustained over the medium term.
</P>
<P>
These concerns include inadequate progress on structural
reforms, perceived inability of some governments to address
macroeconomic imbalances, political uncertainty, and rising world
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
China's Hong Kong, The Republic of Korea and Singapore are
expected to lead in the region with GDP growth in 2000 of 8.5
percent, 8.3 percent and 8 percent respectively, says the report.
</P>
<P>
It estimates that the GDP growth for the whole year of 2000 for
the People's Republic of China is 7.5 percent, based on first half
growth of 8.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Southeast Asia's growth in 2000 is forecast to rise to 4.7
percent from the original projection of 4.6 percent, while the
newly industrialized economies are expected to achieve growth of 7.
9 percent instead of 6.5 percent projected earlier.
</P>
<P>
The report lifts South Asia's GDP growth forecast to 6.5
percent in 2000 by 0.1 percentage point while the Central Asian
Republics' GDP is expected to grow 4.1 percent in the year as
against the 3 percent forecast earlier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assault on Rebels Weighs Down Manila Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Share prices in the Philippine
Stock Exchange ended lower Monday amid the ongoing military
assault against the bandit group, Abu Sayyaf, in the southern
island of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The 30-company Phisix, the market's main index, shed 10.72
points to close at 1,440.27. The broader all-shares index also
lost 1.71 points to 682.80.
</P>
<P>
Dealers exchanged 1.2 billion shares worth some 329.9 million U.
S. dollars on Monday against last Friday's 3.9 billion shares
worth some 13 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the military attacks against the Abu Sayyaf group
which started Saturday dampened further the already dropping
market sentiment.
</P>
<P>
"It came out as a surprise to many. There is news block-out
which keep the people nervous. People want to know what has been
going on with the attack, the safety of the hostages and the
civilians, and further developments of the state in Mindanao,"
said Albert Chua, analyst at All Asia Asset Management. 
</P>
</TEXT>
