<HEADLINE> Xinhua Asia-Pacific Economic News Summary, Monday, September 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesia is seeking around 4.8 billion U.S. dollars
in loans from its traditional international donors grouped under
the Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) to help finance the
budget deficit in 2001, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
That total will include the undisbursed portion of 4.7 billion
dollars loans pledged by CGI to Indonesia for this year, The
Jakarta Post Saturday quoted Coordinating Minister for Economy
Affairs Rizal Ramli as saying.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
JINAN -- The Fourth China Dezhou Investment and Trade Fair
opened today in the city of Dezhou in east China's Shandong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Investors from more than 45 countries and regions as well as 2,
500 business people in China were present at today's opening
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
SHANGHAI -- Shanghai auctioned over 100 pieces of Kuan Yao
Porcelain today at prices over 11 million yuan (approximately 1.3
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
There were 123 pieces for the auction, with almost 100 of the
pieces being provided by Aisingiorro Qimeng, a descendant of
Emperor Daoguang of Qing Dynasty (1644-1911) born in 1968.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time such a large number of Kuan Yao Porcelain
pieces were on auction in China, as the porcelain was rarely
handed down from ancient times.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- Chinese regulatory authorities will loosen their
control on the corporate bonds issuance procedure under a new
management provision that is expected to come out by the end of
the year, reported today's China Daily Business Weekly.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Planning Commission will no longer limit
the issuance volume of corporate bonds under the new provision,
nor will it examine and give opinion on every issue, said a senior
financial expert.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- The People's Bank of China (PBC), China's central
bank, announced last week it would relend 33.3 billion yuan (four
billion U.S. dollars) to rural credit co-operatives.
</P>
<P>
The central bank asked the co-operatives to make full use of
the funds to support agricultural production and increase farmers'
income.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- China will auction about 200,000 tons of cotton
reserve around October 1 to calm down rising price, said an
official with the National Cotton Trade Market.
</P>
<P>
Experts warned cotton growers not to anticipate extraordinarily
high prices and stow their produce.
</P>
<P>
Although China's cotton production is expected to fall short of
demand this year, the government will use its huge cotton stocks
to balance supply and demand, said Zhu Lanfen, director of the
Enterprise Reform Department of the State Textile Industry Bureau.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
SEOUL -- South Korea's foreign exchange reserves have risen to
91.66 billion U.S. dollars by September 15,the Bank of Korea said
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank attributed the rise to the foreign currency
repayments by domestic banks to it and profits accruing from
management of foreign currency assets.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
PHNOM PENH -- The United Kingdom Department for International
Development is providing about 2.1 million U.S. dollars for a
three-year Phnom Penh Urban Poverty Reduction project.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will be working in conjunction with the UN
Development Program, is scheduled to begin November 1.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK -- Thailand and Laos have agreed to jointly push
forward tourism along the Mekong river, a move that will benefit
all countries along the river.
</P>
<P>
A feasibility study of extending the Mekong river tourism
routes from Thailand to Laos will soon be conducted by both sides
following the meeting, it said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Laos have also agreed to extend the Mekong tourism
cooperation plan to all the countries along the river, it added.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR -- The 8th Asia-Pacific Convention of German
Business opened here Monday to serve as a platform for German and
Asian organizations to form smart partnership.
</P>
<P>
The two-day convention "New dynamics in the Asia-Pacific
Region: Innovation-Technology-Cooperation" aims to improve
economic conditions and to encourage a greater commitment of
German organizations in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
PAJU, SOUTH KOREA -- South Korean President Kim Dae-jung
inaugurated the launching of project reconnecting Seoul-Shinuiju
railway at the Imjin-gak pavilion of Paju city, close to the truce
village of Panmunjom on Monday morning.
</P>
<P>
The 486-kilometer railway runs from South Korean capital city
of Seoul to the Shinuiju, a far north city of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The 12-kilometer section linking South Korean city of Munsun
with Changdan just on the Military Demarcation Line will be
completed around September next year at a cost of 54.7 billion won
(some 48 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
----
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japan's three major insurers, Tokio Marine and Fire
Insurance Co., Asahi Mutual Life Insurance Co. and Nichido Fire
and Marine Insurance Co. announced Monday that they plan to form a
comprehensive tie-up with a view to integrating their operations
in the future.
</P>
<P>
The tie-up arrangement came as competition in Japan's insurance
sector intensified following the Japanese government's decision to
give insurers the freedom to compete by offering lower premiums
and innovative policies.
</P>
<P>
The three insurers will immediately create a committee to craft
business strategies for cashing in on the merits springing from
the formation of the new alliance. 
</P>
