<HEADLINE> Heavy Fighting Rages in Northern Sri Lanka Amid Elections Campaigning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting raged in Sri
Lanka's northern Jaffna peninsula on Monday as elections
campaigning was in full swing, military officials said.
</P>
<P>
The separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) launched
counterattacks after government troops on Sunday had recaptured
the town of Chavakachcheri, the second largest one in the Jaffna
peninsula, Military Spokesman S. Karunaratne said.
</P>
<P>
He said government troops had recovered the bodies of 18 LTTE
rebels and another 50 rebels might have been killed.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said around 20 government soldiers had been
killed and some 200 wounded, 68 of them seriously.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of fighting began on Sunday as the island
country prepared for 11th general elections slated for October 10.
Election fever is gripping Jaffna as more than 10 political
parties have handed in their nominations to vie for the nine seats
for the electoral district.
</P>
<P>
Chavakachcheri, the main town between Elephant Pass and Jaffna
on the 53 kilometer main supply route, was captured by the LTTE
rebels in April this year shortly after the fall of the strategic
Elephant Pass.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE rebels are fighting a 17-year war against majority
Sinhalese dominated government in a bid to carve out a separate
state for minority Tamils in the country's north and east. More
than 60,000 people have been killed in the ethnic war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
