<HEADLINE> Philippines Prepares Emergency Medical Teams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Philippine health authorities
have prepared emergency medical teams in the provinces of Cotabato
and Zamboanga to take care of civilians that may be affected by
ongoing police and military action against the Abu Sayyaf in Jolo.
</P>
<P>
Secretary Alberto Romualdez of the Department of Health said
Monday that these emergency teams will coordinate with the
National Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) in undertaking these
efforts.
</P>
<P>
"We are coordinating with the NDCC and we are organizing teams.
Once there are victims, we'll send people to the Cotabato and
Zamboanga Medical Centers and help out our integrated health
office in Sulu," Romualdez said in a radio interview.
</P>
<P>
He also said military health personnel are in charge of the
situation in Jolo, and that civilian health officials are giving
them full support.
</P>
<P>
President Estrada ordered last Saturday a police and military
strike on Abu Sayyaf lairs in Jolo, Sulu province to rescue l9
hostages still in the hands of the extremist group.
</P>
<P>
"I thick we'll be ready for any contingency. We're worried
about the possibility of displaced persons generated by the
renewed conflict," Romualdez said.
</P>
<P>
The government has assured the public that the rescue
operations are confined to specific areas, although a news
blackout was imposed to prevent the telegraphing of government
moves.
</P>
<P>
Romualdez said local health offices have sufficient medical
supplies to meet the needs of affected residents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
