<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandela to Visit Burundian Refugees to Explain Peace Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
President Nelson Mandela, mediator in the Burundi crisis, next
month will visit all Burundian refugee camps in western Tanzania
to explain the peace accord signed in Tanzania's northern town of
Arusha on August 28, newspapers here reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's top aid, leader of the facilitation team, Mark Bomani,
was quoted as saying here on Sunday that Mandela would be
accompanied by all signatories of the Arusha peace agreement to
camps in Tanzania's western Kagera and Kigoma regions that host
hundreds of thousands of Burundian refugees.
</P>
<P>
The refugees would be told about what was discussed in all
negotiation meetings for Burundi peace for the last two years as
they are ignorant of the contents and implications of the peace
accord, Bomani said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, he said, they had been subjected to various
uncoordinated information inside the camps through the mass media
and a few individuals.
</P>
<P>
The delegates would also explain to refugees all resolutions so
far reached concerning the Arusha peace agreement and how it was
going to be effectively implemented, he said, adding that the
delegates would later visit Burundi for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
The Burundians need not to worry about the agreement, said
Bomani, saying that it tries to meet the aspirations and concerns
of all the concerned parties.
</P>
<P>
"We're aware that this document is not perfect. It is neither a
Bible nor a Koran, it can be modified by those who signed it," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that arrangements to repatriate refugees would be
made soon to enable refugees willing to go back home do so without
any delay.
</P>
<P>
"This will be a voluntary exercise. No one will be forced to go
back to Burundi," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the monitoring committee to supervise the
implementation of the peace agreement would be formed soon. It
would comprise 12 members, including nine Burundi nationals and
three members from the United Nations, the Organization of African
Unity and the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
If implemented, the agreement would put in place a transitional
government in three to six months, create a new upper house of
parliament and split the country's army equally between Hutus and
Tutsis.
</P>
<P>
Civil war between the two ethnic groups began in 1993 and has
taken the lives of around 200,000 people, mostly civilians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
