<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Kills Nine in Russia's Far East </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Nine people were killed and
76 wounded in road accidents caused by a typhoon in Russia's Far
East territory of Maritime over the past weekend.
</P>
<P>
They are victims of a total of 55 road mishaps during the
typhoon raging in the area, including nine children, the Itar-Tass
news agency quoted local traffic police as saying Monday.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon also seriously damaged the local power supplying
system. Heavy rains inundated coal mines in Luchegorsk, and the
reduction of hydro electric station capacity led to electricity
cut-off throughout the Primorye region.
</P>
<P>
Storms and strong wind with a speed of 25 meters a second,
damaged power supplying in several other regions in the Maritime
territory, an official of the administration in the Pacific port-
city of Vladivostok said.
</P>
<P>
Overturned trees blocked traffic and broke electricity
transmission lines in Vladivostok. 60 people have been evacuated
from the settlement of Putsylovka in the Ussuriisk region after
the local river overflowed its banks and flooded the area, said
the territorial emergency center.
</P>
<P>
Monday, the rains have suspended and repair works began in
some key places. But specialists predicted new hard rains will hit
the territory again and cause more floods of rivers, said the
center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
