<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hoogenband Denies Thorpe Third Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Dutch wonder boy Pieter van
den Hoogenband upset Australian mega star Ian Thorpe to win a
thrilling Olympic men's 200m freestyle final here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Van den Hoogenband touched home first in one minute 43.35
seconds, tying his own world record set Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
Denied a third gold medal, Thorpe took silver 24 hours after
Van den Hoogenband broke Thorpe's world record in the semis.
</P>
<P>
Thorpe finished in 1:45.83 and Massimiliano Rosolino of Italy
was third in 1:46.65.
</P>
<P>
Lenny Krayzelburg gave the United States its fourth gold in
three days of swimming, winning the 100m backstroke in an Olympic
record 53.72 seconds.
</P>
<P>
He broke the old mark of 53.86 set by American Jeff Rouse at
the 1992 Olympics, but was 0.12 seconds away from his own world
record set in the same pool last year.
</P>
<P>
Matthew Welsh of Australia took silver in 54.07, while Stev
Theloke of Germany won bronze in 54.82.
</P>
<P>
Van den Hoogenband fought with Thorpe stroke by stroke until
the 150m mark when the Dutchman began pulling away.
</P>
<P>
Van den Hoogenband jumped to fame last year by beating Olympic
champion Alexander Popov of Russia in the 50 and 100 freestyles at
the European championships.
</P>
<P>
"I gave it my all in the race," Thorpe said. "That was a great
race on behalf of Pieter. It's a real privilege to be able to swim
that race."
</P>
<P>
Diana Mocanu became the first Romanian swimmer to win a gold
medal, taking the 100m backstroke in an Olympic record 1:00.21.
</P>
<P>
Mai Nakamura came second in 1:00.55 with Nina Zhivanevskaya of
Spain third in 1:00.89. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
