<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Unearths Stone Relic With Cuneiform Inscription </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Iranian archaeologists on
Sunday unearthed a stone relic inscribed in cuneiform on the
historical Hegmataneh hill of the western city of Hamedan, the
official Islamic Republic News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The relic, uncovered after 11 years of excavation, is believed
to be part of the capital (crown) of an ancient pedestal, said
Mohammad Rahim Sarraf, head of the excavation team, adding that it
was the first such discovery in Iran.
</P>
<P>
The inscription provides proof of the existence of palaces
belonging to Achamenean kings who lived in Hegmataneh, one of the
most ancient cities known in the world.
</P>
<P>
The Achamenid dynasty ruled Persia (ancient Iran) during 553-330
B.C..
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists hope the inscription would help bring out the
identity of the ancient kings who laid the foundations of early
civilization in Hegmataneh, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
