<HEADLINE> Zambian President Orders Removal of Squatters Occupying Land Illegally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba has warned that the government would not condone people
occupying land illegally, Zambia Daily Mail newspaper reported on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The president, who was back from a tour to Ndola, Copperbelt
Province on Sunday, has ordered the immediate removal of squatters
occupying and developing land illegally and warned of severe
consequences against the law breakers.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Lusaka Province Minister Sonny Mulenga has directed
police to arrest people putting up structures without title deeds
on the disputed land in suburban Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
Mulenga also called on the squatters to use right channels to
obtain plots rather than violence, adding that the government had
a responsibility to issue land and that it would not abandon the
squatters.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that land grabbers in Chazanga area have been
fighting running battles with local villagers who were given the
land by Chieftainess Mungule in 1960.
</P>
<P>
The squatters want to grab part of the vast tracts of land,
stating that they had no financial capacity to pay rentals to
their landlords in Chazanga.
</P>
<P>
Last Friday, Chzanga residents and villagers clashed in a fight
that left at least four villagers seriously beaten, including one
man unconscious.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday residents from the two areas clashed over the
disputed land when about 700 squatters stormed what is perceived
as customary land. 
</P>
</TEXT>
