<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 15, 300 Kenyan Children Die of Vitamin A Deficiency Annually </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Some 15, 300 Kenyan children
aged below six years die annually due to Vitamin A Deficiency (VAD)
, according to the country's first national survey on the vitamin.
</P>
<P>
Thousands more become blind for life due to lack of the vitamin
while others suffer chronic illnesses that impact negatively on
their long-term survival and productivity, the East African weekly
reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A report on the survey said that VAD is one of the leading
causes of childhood mortality in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
"Thirty-three percent of Kenyan children are marginally vitamin
A deficient, which, according to the World Health Organization's (
WHO) criteria, constitutes a grave national health problem," the
report said.
</P>
<P>
The survey, involving a total of 6,425 children, was conducted
in 14 districts spread over Kenya's eight provinces by researchers
from Moi University and the Kenya Medical Research Institute.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that children aged between six to two years
are at the risk of suffering from VAD, probably due to weaning
before they are able to eat green vegetables, the leading source
of vitamin A in Kenya.
</P>
<P>
It also established that xerophthalimia, or damage to the eye
due to VAD, is more common in boys than girls.
</P>
<P>
According to the WHO, it is estimated that VAD affects 2.8 to
three million pre-school children worldwide critically, and up to
250 million others severely or moderately.
</P>
<P>
Researchers involved in the survey recommended that in Kenya,
there is a need to formulate a policy that addresses the problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
