<HEADLINE> Roundup: Bangladeshi Teachers Continues Indefinite Strike  by Pan Xiaozhu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Classes in 23 thousand non-
government primary schools across the country could not be held
for the 17th consecutive day on Monday due to the continuing
indefinite work abstention program of the teachers of the
respective institutions.
</P>
<P>
Expressing dismay over the inaction of the government to end
the deadlock through negotiation, the leaders of the striking
teachers made it clear that they would continue their action
program till the realization of their demands. And such rigid
stand of the leaders has caused deep concern among the guardians
of over 0.8 million school-going students across the country.
</P>
<P>
Some 93,000 teachers of 23,000 registered and non-registered
primary schools across the country went on strike for an
indefinite period from September 2 demanding nationalization of
their respective institutions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, in January this year, the non-government primary
school teachers staged a sit-in demonstration in the capital to
press home their "one-point demand" for nationalization of all non-
government primary school. But the government did not respond
positively.
</P>
<P>
The teachers' leaders made an appeal to the government on
August 23 to accept their demand by August 31. Otherwise, they
threatened to go for an indefinite strike from September 2.
</P>
<P>
As part of the movement to press home their demand, the
striking teachers will stage a sit-in demonstration around the
Prime Minister's Secretariat on September 25.
</P>
<P>
A high official of the Education Ministry Saturday termed the
strike illegal, saying that a section of teachers were out to
create disarray in the education sector under the cover of so-
called movement. The official said that the government is
determined not to bow down to any pressure by accepting the unjust
demands of the teachers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
