<HEADLINE> Sanitation in Uganda's Schools Alarming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Less than 30 percent of
schools and institutions of higher learning in Uganda have got
access to clean and safe water, the New Vision daily reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The sanitation and environment in most schools in the country
is in a sorry state which puts learners' lives in danger, the
newspaper quoted Head of the School Health Department in the
Ministry of Health Jeremiah Twatawa as saying.
</P>
<P>
Twatawa said that very few schools have got permanent supplies
of safe drinking water and as a result, school children end up
drinking from dirty and unsafe water sources near the schools.
</P>
<P>
Many school latrines are inadequate, inappropriate and
dangerous, which makes students' lives prone to diseases, he said,
adding that in some instances, the toilets are so open that
adolescents fear to use them.
</P>
<P>
Diseases like intestinal worms and other water borne diseases
are prevalent among school children because of this, said Twatwa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
