<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Health Delivery System Restructuring underway  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The recommended structure provides for a new finance department
and will also see central and provincial hospitals become self-
governing institutions.
</P>
<P>
All the country's four central hospitals will now be headed by
chief executive officers reporting to a hospital management board.
Medical superintendents at provincial hospitals will also report
to advisory boards. The management or advisory boards report
directly to the health minister.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with The Herald on Sunday, Minister of Health
and Child Welfare Timothy Stamps said the idea to decentralize
management of health services seeks to involve local communities.
</P>
<P>
Although he would have liked to see the process accelerated,
Stamps admitted that a lot of money would be needed to get the
project moving forward.
</P>
<P>
The minister said, "We have realized that we cannot run
everything from central government. We will not get a solution to
the health problems until all stakeholders are involved."
</P>
<P>
He said the restructuring exercise envisages a situation where
health committees at district level would also run outreach
activities.
</P>
<P>
At least 60 district hospitals would be involved in the
exercise, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
