<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Tony Estanguet of France got
the men's C1 canoe-kayak gold medal here on Monday at the Olympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
"I was well prepared," said the Frenchman, who scored 231.87
points, and revealed on his feelings after having touched the gate
that "After touching it, I knew that I had to go on the attack."
</P>
<P>
On his opinion of the last section of the course, Estanguet
said that "I know it was really hard, but it was really hard for
everyone."
</P>
<P>
Estanguet said that "I wasn't thinking about a gold medal. I
was thinking about all the things that lead up to the Olympic
Games. There are lots of people in it, lots of great coaches.
I've got a good coach and also good parents."
</P>
<P>
The silver medal went to Michal Martikan of Slovakia with 233.
76 and his compatriot Juraj Mincik finished third in 234.22.
</P>
<P>
Martikan said that "I was happy with my first run, even though
it was hard. I was able to do something better in the second run.
Unfortunately, it was my first run which let me down. It is
disappointing to miss gold, but I feel good to have won a medal."
</P>
<P>
On the final couse, he said that "it was faster than the
qualifications course. The Olympics is a different type of feeling,
a different type of race."
</P>
<P>
He also hailed Estanguet of his victory, saying that "he had a
good first run, which he made the most of. If I had a better first
run I could have run." 
