<HEADLINE> Death Toll of Floods in Vietnam's Mekong Delta Reaches 13 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The floods that have hit
Vietnam's Mekong Delta over the past two months caused the death
of at least 13 people, local daily Vietnam News (VNS) reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The floods with the waters hitting their highest level in 40
years in the delta have also driven 150,000 others from their
houses.
</P>
<P>
150,000 people have already taken refuge on dikes and another
500,000 people's homes are fully or partly submerged, VNS quoted
the Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies delegation
chief, John Geoghegan, as saying.
</P>
<P>
The floodwaters Sunday morning hit 4.94 meters and 4.71 meters
respectively in Tan Chau and Chau Doc districts in the delta's
province of An Giang.
</P>
<P>
Waters in the lower parts of the Mekong river, the Tien and Hau
tributaries, are still rising. They reached 1.59 meters and 1.63
meters respectively in the provinces of My Thuan and Can Tho on
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
Floodwaters have turned large areas of the country's three
worst-hit provinces of Dong Thap, An Giang ang Tien Giang, which
border Cambodia, into inland seas and more rain is expected in the
coming days.  
</P>
</TEXT>
