<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Political Parties' Conference Opens in Manila </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The First International
Conference of Asian Political Parties formally opened Monday in
Manila where leaders from about 40 political parties will discuss
political and economic cooperation in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
De Venecia, chairman of the conference's organizing committee,
said at the opening ceremony that the vision of the two-day
conference is to create a culture of cooperation among Asia's
parties and hasten the region's economic and political integration.
</P>
<P>
"Our purpose is to begin a process of fraternal consultations --
to found a culture of cooperation among our parties -- and to
promote political cooperation in Asia over the first decades of
the 21st century," said De Venecia, former speaker of the
Philippine House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
Citing the experience of the European Union, De Venecia said
Asia's political parties should look beyond the current regional
organizations "toward an Asian Parliament, an Asian monetary fund,
an Asian common market, and an Asian currency."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Asia's leaders "must raise strong political
will" to face the parties' "greatest challenges" which he
identified as completing the region's "agricultural and industrial
modernization, eradicating mass-poverty, controlling corruption,
and enabling our peoples to cope with the technological and
knowledge revolution."
</P>
<P>
In his remark, De Venecia also called for a new global
Christian-Muslim partnership and dialogue in the light of ethnic
and politico-religious conflicts in Asia and other parts of the
world.
</P>
<P>
"Let us look into the feasibility of a global Christian-Muslim
coalition at the level of political parties, to help resolve
ethnic and politico-religious conflicts which have now spilled
over into the 21st century," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asia's senior leaders, including Prince Norodom Ranarridh from
Cambodia, former Pakistani Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto, former
South Korean President Kim Young Sam, and Speaker of the
Bangladesh Parliament Humayun Rasheed Choudhury, also made their
statements on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The political parties attending the conference are from
Bangladesh, Cambodia, China, East Timor, India, Indonesia, Iran,
Japan, South Korea, Laos, Malaysia, Mongolia, Myanmar, Nepal,
Pakistan, Papua New Guinea, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand
and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada is scheduled to meet the
delegates and deliver his address at a dinner-reception at the
Presidential Palace Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, some 170 delegates from the political parties will
discuss different topics in three simultaneous workshops while a
committee will finalize the draft of the joint Asian Declaration
which is scheduled to be signed Tuesday afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
