<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0293 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Entire Bangladesh Except Barisal to be Under Railway Network </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
DHAKA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The entire Bangladesh except
the greater Barisal district, 277 kilometers south of Dhaka, has
been planned to be connected through railway network within the
next two years, according to the Bangladesh Observer Monday.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Railway sources were quoted as saying that the
state owned railway was spending and also plans to spend a total
of 278 million U.S. dollars for the expansion of its network and
improvement of services aimed at restoring the past glory of
railway communication.
</P>
<P>
After years of gradual dwindling in the length of its track,
Bangladesh railways is now hopeful of not only reversing the trend,
but also adding substantial kilometers to its track length, the
sources said.
</P>
<P>
Following the independence, the total length of railway track
in the country in 1972 was 2,858 kilometers. The track length came
down to 2,706 kilometers in 1992-93, a situation which continue
till 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
However, the trend was reversed and during the past four years
47 kilometers have already been added and more are in progress.
</P>
<P>
The work on the two projects for "Jamuna Bridge rail
connection" at a cost of around 148 million dollars have already
begun. Construction of a 99 kilometers rail-route in the
northwestern part of the country at a cost of 95 million dollars
is in progress and will be completed in June next year. The
conversion of 245 kilometers track from Serajganj to Parbatipur,
also in the northwestern part of the country, at a cost of 50.7
million dollars which began in December 1999 will be completed in
March 2002 as per schedule.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh Railways in recent years involved private sector
for improvement in the management of commercial activities of
mail and local trains. The steps have proved to be effective and
remunerative for the railways as more passengers now feel
encouraged to use railways.
</P>
<P>
The process of integrating private sector in railway
activities began in 1997 and presently 10 pairs of train run daily
under private supervision. Process is now almost completed for
operating commercial activities in another 31 pairs of trains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
