<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Yang Xia Wins Women's 53kg Weightlifting Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- China showed their amazing
depth in women's weightlifting as Yang Xia won the 53kg category
with three world records at the 27th Olympic Games on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Yang, 23, who has never won a gold in major world competitions
except the 1998 Asian Games, broke snatch, jerk and total world
marks with 100kg, 125kg and 225kg respectively, before winning the
gold medal.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Taipei's Li Fengying, who previously held the world
jerk record of 121.5kg, finished second in a total of. Slamet
Winarni Binti Slamet of Indonesia took the bronze in 202kg.
</P>
<P>
The previous world records of snatch and total were 97.5kg and
217.5kg, which were both held by another Chinese Meng Xianjuan.
</P>
<P>
Yang met almost no challenge during the competition but former
fellow Chinese teammate Li, now representing Chinese Taipei. Li
snatched 97.5kg and jerked 115kg to take the silver with a total
of 212.5kg.
</P>
<P>
"I felt very relaxed in the competition," Yang said. "It's like
a match at home. The jerk result of 125kg was even lower than my
personal best."
</P>
<P>
Yang gave up her third attempt in the jerk after a 125kg lift
in the second attempt had anchored her the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
"Her performance was fantastic and fully demonstrated China's
leading position in the sport," said Zhang Wenxi, head coach of
Chinese women's weightlifting team.
</P>
<P>
Li, the world snatch champion in 1994, finished runner-up to
Yang in her first international competition after turning to
Chinese Taipei. She claimed two gold medals in the snatch and
total at last year's Athens World Champions in the absence of Yang.
</P>
<P>
"Li's silver is the third Olympic weightlifting medal for
Chinese Taipei in history. We're very, very happy to win the medal,
" said Chang Chao-Kuo, president of the Chinese Taipei
Weightlifting Association. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
