<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Firms to Maintain Intensive Contracts with ASEAN Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 18 (Xinhua) -- German Economics and
Technology Minister Werner Muller said here Monday German firms
want to maintain intensive business contracts with all ASEAN
countries.
</P>
<P>
Quite a few German companies are already orienting themselves
to an ASEAN market of 500 million consumers and have positioned
themselves accordingly, he said at the opening of the two-day 8th
Asia-Pacific Convention of German Business here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Praising ASEAN as the most effective regional association in
the Asia-Pacific area, he however said ASEAN did not provide the
desire level of consistency during the recent financial crisis,
even though there was an advanced degree of economic integration
between the market-oriented ASEAN members in particular.
</P>
<P>
He held that the economic systems and economic policies of the
various ASEAN countries still diverge too greatly for a process of
economic integration to commerce.
</P>
<P>
A uniform market framework is needed, not just as a
precondition and basis for intensified ASEAN cooperation, the
German minister said, adding "Competition under globalized market
condition also makes this structural adjustment necessary."
</P>
<P>
"The need for structural change in some ASEAN countries is one
reason why there is still more potential for trade with Germany
and for German investment in these countries," he said, hoping the
process of market reforms would speed up.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN formed in 1967 now groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia,
Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
