<HEADLINE> Ethiopians, Kenyans Battle for Men's 10,000m in Olympics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Defending Olympic champion
Haile Gebreselassie of Ethiopia is known as the "master" over 10,
000 meters and is undefeated at this event since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Gebreselassie holds the Olympic record of 27:07.34 set in
Atlanta and has also run 15 world records. At age of 27, he
should be at his running prime. The only doubt is whether he has
been able to regain full fitness after an injury early this year.
</P>
<P>
Paul Tergat of Kenya chose not to run the Kenyan Championships
at 10,000 meters, and was originally selected for the 5,000 meters.
However, after running the year's fastest time of 27:03.87 at
Brussels on August 25, he switched to this event.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan champion is John Korir, who, at age of 18, is still
a junior, and the third top Kenyan is Patrick Ivuti.
</P>
<P>
Two more Ethiopians will be in contention -- Assefa mezgebu,
the 1999 African Games 10,000m winner, who was third at Seville in
1999, and second in the 2000 World Cross Country Race, and Girma
Tula who was fourth in Seville.
</P>
<P>
Mohammed Mourhit of Belgium set a European record fo 26:52.30
last year, and although he has not contested a 10,000m this year,
will be a major threat if he runs this event.
</P>
<P>
Another to attract attention is Jose Rios of Spain who won the
Spanish title in August in 27:22.70. 
</P>
