<HEADLINE> Thailand, Laos Agree to Boost Mekong River Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Laos have agreed
to jointly push forward tourism along the Mekong river, a move
that will benefit all countries along the river, a report from
Thai government said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
At yesterday's meeting between Thai Minister of Prime Minister'
s Office Adisai Bhodaramik and Lao Tourism Authority chairman
Cheng Sayavong in Vientiane, the Lao capital, both sides held the
same opinion that the Mekong river, which runs from China through
Myanmar, Thailand, Laos, Cambodia and Vietnam will become a
favorite destination for tourists interested in the region's
abundant historical sites, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
A feasibility study of extending the Mekong river tourism
routes from Thailand to Laos will soon be conducted by both sides
following the meeting, it said.
</P>
<P>
The Thai-Lao cooperation in the Mekong tourism will help Laos
attract more foreign tourists, as people who travel in the region
will be able to extend their trips to Laos, it said.
</P>
<P>
The number of visitors to Laos last year was recorded at 614,
278, up 24 percent from the year before. Thai visitors topped the
list by accounting for 57 percent of all the tourists, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand and Laos have also agreed to extend the Mekong tourism
cooperation plan to all the countries along the river, it added.
</P>
</TEXT>
