<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economy Expands 5 Percent in Second Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Thai economy grew about five
percent in the second quarter of this year, The Nation newspaper
reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi was quoted as
saying that the National Economic and Social Development Board (
NESDB) had already handed him its economic report, but he would
not disclose the exact rate of economic growth until later Monday.
</P>
<P>
"The rate of economic growth in the second quarter did not
change much from the first one, and the average rate of growth in
the first half of the year is not less than 5 percent," Supachai
said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's economy expanded 5.2 percent year-on-year in the
first quarter. The NESDB had earlier forecast that the economy
would grow by 5 per cent this year.
</P>
<P>
Supachai said that the higher price of oil would result in
lower economic growth in the third and fourth quarters. However,
the government will achieve its previous projection of a five-
percent growth this year because the negative effect of higher oil
prices would be offset by higher export growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's exports grew 17 percent in the first eight months of
this year. The commerce ministry has forecast that export growth
this year would exceed a previous projection of 12 percent and
rise to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
Supachai expressed concern over the price of oil and the wide
interest rate spread, which has adversely affected consumption.
</P>
<P>
"The government will not intervene in the central bank's
interest rate policy, but we will ask the central bank why
commercial banks have brought down the saving rates, but have kept
higher lending rates," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Such an interest rate policy will not boost the economy;
either the lending rates are brought down or the saving rates must
be brought up."
</P>
<P>
Almost all of the Thai commercial banks have maintained higher
lending rates of between eight and 8.75 percent while cutting the
saving rates to between 2.25 and 3.75 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
Regarding the possibility of a cut in the oil tax, Supachai
said this would be the government's last option because even a one-
baht (2.4 U.S. cents) concession in the levy would result in a
revenue loss of 20 billion baht (487 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
