<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Launches Project to Protect Eroding Coastline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka has launched a 80
million U.S. dollars Coastal Resources Management Project to
protect its eroding coastline and instill sustainable management
practices, the official Daily News reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank would provide a concessional loan of
40 million dollars to the project while the government of the
Netherlands will contribute 12.76 million dollars as a grant, said
the paper, adding that the government of Sri Lanka will fund the
balance of the project.
</P>
<P>
The project, which will be completed by 2005, is considered
vital to the survival of much of Sri Lanka's coastal environment.
The western and southern coast alone is estimated to lose between
200,000 to 300,000 square meters of beach a year to storms and
high waves.
</P>
<P>
The coast is home to one third of the country's 19 million
population and the highly productive ecosystem is an important
base for the country's growth. The coastal zone accounts for
nearly 80 percent of fish production and 70 percent of industrial
output. The eroding coastline specially endangers economic
activity on the densely populated western and southwestern coast.
</P>
<P>
The project will construct shoreline protection works in the
most affected coastline in six districts along the northwestern,
western and southwestern coasts. It will also address other major
problems such as overfishing, pollution, uncontrolled exploitation
of lagoons and estuaries, coral reefs and mangrove swamps, grass
beds and other wetlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0326 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea Launches Inter-Korea Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PAJU, SOUTH KOREA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- South Korean
President Kim Dae-jung inaugurated the launching of project
reconnecting Seoul-Shinuiju railway at the Imjin-gak pavilion of
Paju city, close to the truce village of Panmunjom on Monday
morning.
</P>
<P>
The president said,"this is a new starting point for the
history of our people toward a new era of reconciliation,
cooperation and prosperity,"
</P>
<P>
The reconstruction of the 12-kilometer section linking the two
sides railways was decided by Kim Dae-jung and DPRK leader Kim
Jong Il in Pyongyang on June 15 in a historic South-North Joint
Declaration.
</P>
<P>
The 486-kilometer railway runs from South Korean capital city
of Seoul to the Shinuiju, a far north city of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
The 12-kilometer section linking South Korean city of Munsun
with Changdan just on the Military Demarcation Line will be
completed around September next year at a cost of 54.7 billion won
(some 48 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The DPRK will build the north side of the section from Kaesong
city to Changdan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the construction of a new highway linking Munsun and
Changdan also started Monday and is also expected to be concluded
next September with an investment of 100 billion won (some 88
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Relinking the inter-Korean railway system, which was severed
before the Korean War in early 1950s, is believed to be a concrete
step forward to full-scale economic cooperation between Seoul and
Pyongyang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
