<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Conference on Children Closes with Important Achievements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 17 (Xinhua) -- The week-long International
Conference on War-Affected Children drew to a close Sunday in
Winnipeg with a deal to free abducted African children and a 14-
point plan to safeguard the rights of children.
</P>
<P>
Through the mediation of Canada and Egypt, Sudan and Uganda
agreed to cooperate in repatriating an estimated 6,000 Ugandan
children abducted by the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA), a rebel
force in Sudan.
</P>
<P>
"We are very encouraged by the commitment of the Government of
Sudan to work to ensure the release and safe return of these
abducted children," said Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
"The undertaking by the Government of Uganda to provide
conditions conducive to the reconciliation, rehabilitation, return
and resettlement of members of the LRA is a key aspect in solving
this tragic situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister also announced "the upcoming release of 16
abductees" as "an important step" for the entire process to free
the abducted children.
</P>
<P>
The deal is the latest development in the relations between
Sudan and Uganda, which have been for year accusing each other of
supporting rebel forces. International mediation has been
conducted on several occasions to help resolve disputes between
the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Canadian International Cooperation Minister Maria
Minna announced that the Canadian International Development Agency
(CIDA) will invest at least 1 million Canadian dollars (about 672,
300 U.S. dollars) to help released children re-integrate into
their communities.
</P>
<P>
The conference, among others, adopted a 14-point plan calling
for "political, moral, economic and social leadership" to
safeguard the rights of children.
</P>
<P>
The conference, the first of its kind, has attracted ministers,
representatives and experts from more than 130 countries. The
adopted documents will be presented to the United Nation's Special
Session on Children next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
