<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romanian Lifters Allowed to Stay at Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Three male and one female
weightlifters from Romanian team have got a permission to stay at
the Sydney Olympic Games after payment of a 50,000 U.S. dollars
fine, team officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
Romanian head coach Niku Vlad said:"We paid it (the fine)
because it was not fiar that the other athletes should go home."
</P>
<P>
The Romanians had been suspended under a International
Weightlifting Federation (IWF) rule which says that if three or
more lifters give positive results in a season, the national
association should be suspended from international competitions
for a year.
</P>
<P>
The country's National Olympic Committee has now paid the IWF
the fine to keep their four "clean" weightlifters in the
competition.
</P>
<P>
Vlad said a Romanian was due to take part in the weightlifting
events later on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Earlier the International Olympic Committee (IOC) had said the
weightlifting team should leave the Games because of the doping
offences and ruled out any chance of a reprieve.
</P>
<P>
But IOC director general Francois Carrard later said
eligibility was a matter for the international federations.
</P>
<P>
He was unaware of the IWF's decision to allow the Romanians
back in.
</P>
<P>
But he said: "We always follow the decision of the
international federation unless there is something extraordinary
to reconsider it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
