<HEADLINE> Indonesian President Orders Soeharto's Guards to be Disarmed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President
Abdurrahman Wahid has instructed security forces to disarm former
president Soeharto's bodyguards, local press reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
"I have asked the head of the intelligence agency, and later (
will ask) the Indonesian armed forces chief and the national
police chief to ensure all security guards at former president
Soeharto's home who are not members of the armed forces or the
police are disarmed," the Indonesian Observer daily quoted the
president as saying.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in the North Sumatra provincial capital of Medan on
Sunday, Wahid said firearm-carrying individuals could "pretend to
defend themselves, pretend to defend the government, but basically
undermine the government."
</P>
<P>
Wahid gave Soeharto's private guards one week to hand over
their firearms to the government.
</P>
<P>
"If they don't want to, we will look for them until we get them.
That is the only way," he said.
</P>
<P>
The president also said his order was made in connection with
the recent bomb attacks and sectarian violence in the country.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, a powerful explosion rocked the 34-story
Jakarta Stock Exchange building, leaving at least 15 people dead
and dozens of others injured. This is the fourth bomb blasts in
Jakarta in the past three months.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Wahid said that "drastic measures" against those
responsible for the incidents had to be taken to prevent similar
ones from taking place again.
</P>
<P>
Wahid said last Friday he had ordered police to arrest Soeharto
's Youngest son Hutomo Mandala Putra over the bombing of the
Jakarta Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Following the president's order, Hutomo was questioned last
Saturday by the police but has not been arrested. 
</P>
</TEXT>
