<HEADLINE> Australian O'Neill Tops Women's 200m Freestyle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Susie O'Neill of Australia,
ranked number one in the world, qualified fastest on Monday in the
women's 200m freestyle heats with a time of 1:59.14 at the Olympic
Games.
</P>
<P>
Helen Muller of the United States set a new South African
national record of 1:59.89 from lane two in heat four to be second
fastest, while defending Olympic and world champion Claudia Poll
of Costa Rica posted a time of 2:00.11 to win heat five and
finished third fastest overall.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Franziska van Almsick of Germany, silver
medalist in 1992 and 1996, qualified seventh with a time of 2:00.
37 in heat five.
</P>
<P>
Almsick's world record time of 1:56.78 was never seriously
challenged in any of the heats.
</P>
<P>
Muller however swam the first 100m of her heat under Olympic
record time with splits of 27.57 at 50m and 57.31 at 100m, but
slowed considerably over the last lap of the race. 
