<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Traffic Jam Delays Start of Softball Match </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A traffic jam caused by an
accident delayed the start of the women's softball medal round
match between Japan and China at the Sydney Olympic Games on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese team was delayed for nearly an hour and the start
time was pushed back for nearly an hour.
</P>
<P>
The game started 40 minutes late but the match between the
United States and Cuba, which followed the China-Japan game, was
expected to start as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
An accident on the M4 highway held up the bus carrying the
Japanese team on its way to the Blacktown Olympic Center. The
International Softball Federation granted the Japanese request for
extra time to warm up.
</P>
<P>
"They got there. We are trying to do everything we can," said
Liz Smylie of the SOCOG Sydney organizing committee.
</P>
<P>
Smylie said 50,000 people were in the western region of the
Sydney area where the softball games are played. Part of the
problem, she said, was the lack of a reserved Olympic lane in the
area.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
