<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cai Yalin Wins Men's 10m Air Rifle Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Chinese sharpshooter Cai Yalin
defeated his rivals to win the men's shooting 10m air rifle gold
medal at the Sydney Olympic Games here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 23-year-old Chinese, who led the qualifying round with 594
points, shot consistently in the final and took the crown with 696.
4 points, a new Olympic record.
</P>
<P>
Artem Khadjibekov of Russia was second at 695.1 and his
teammate Evgueni Aleinikov was third at 693.8.
</P>
<P>
In the finals, China's Cai had more than 10 points in each shot
except the last. After nine rounds, Cai margined his nearest
rival by 2.2 points, meaning that a 8.8 point could be enough in
the final shot to assure him the gold.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Games gold medalist rubbed his right hand in
preparation for the final shot, in which he had 9.6 points.
</P>
<P>
Cai Yalin said his coach helped him a lot to win the gold. "My
coach always told me to perform well and that's what I did today,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
On getting over his shaky middle final shots, Cai added:"At the
8th and 9th shots, I didn't do too well and I was a bit concerned.
But I've been training very hard for the last five years and I did
very well."
</P>
<P>
Chinese team manager applauded the gold medal, saying that it
was a breakthrough for Chinese men's rifle sport.
</P>
<P>
It was an unlucky day for gold medal favourite Dirk Boschman of
the Netherlands, who shot a six in his last string to rule him out
of the final.
</P>
<P>
Boschman shot two perfect strings (100) before crashing out of
medal contention, finishing with a disappointing 586.
</P>
<P>
Among other shooters who failed to qualify was Tavarit
Majcharcheep of Thailand, who in the Asian Championships in
January became the first to achieve a perfect score (600/600).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
