<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: Top of the Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to figures released by the National Bureau of
Statistics on September 11, total industrial output value for the
January-August period amounted to 1,496.8 billion yuan (about 180
billion U.S. dollars), 11.6 percent more than in the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign trade volume hit 301.7 billion U.S. dollars in
the first eight months of this year, up 36.7 percent compared with
the figure for the same 1999 period, according to the latest
statistics released here on September 13.
</P>
<P>
According to the General Administration of Customs, the export
volume in January-August reached 159.3 billion U.S. dollars, a
year-on-year rise of 34.6 percent, and the import volume was 142.4
billion U.S. dollars, up 39.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the State Administration of Religious Affairs
on September 13 refuted the slander about China's religious
situation in the 2000 Report on International Religious Freedom by
the U.S. State Department.
</P>
<P>
"The report vilifies China's policy of religious freedom by
distorting facts and spreading rumors," the spokesman said,
stressing that the U.S. government is "grossly interfering in
China's internal affairs" under the pretext of religion, and that
China is "extremely indignant" about it.
</P>
<P>
Tong Jianming, a senior officer with the Ministry of Public
Security, disclosed in Beijing on September 13 that Chinese police
inspected more than 850,000 recreational arcades across the
country during the ongoing nationwide campaign against
prostitution, gambling, drug abuse and trafficking, which was
kicked off July 1, and revoked business licenses to some 50,000
recreational arcades that were found to have violated relevant
administrative rules and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Cheng Kejie was executed in Beijing on September 14 by the No.
1 Intermediate People's Court of Beijing, after the confirmation
and approval by China's Supreme People's Court.
</P>
<P>
Cheng, a former vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, was sentenced to death with all
political rights stripped for life on July 31 at the first
instance trial by the intermediate people's court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
