<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Following are highlights of
today's major Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- China's top legislator Li Peng arrived in Vladivostok Sunday
to continue his official visit to Russia.
</P>
<P>
Vladivostok, the administrative center of Primorsky Territory,
or Maritime Territory, is the last stop of the nine-day Russia
visit by Li, chairman of the Standing Committee of the Chinese
National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
-- Tao Luna won China the first gold medal at the ongoing
Sydney Olympics as she scored a winning score of 488.2 in the
women's 10m air pistol on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Tao was never challenged for the lead, shooting consistently
throughout the 10-shot final, while Jasna Sekaric of Yugoslavia
and Australian Annemarie Forder finished second and third
respectively.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- China's forest coverage rate has reached 16.55 percent
thanks to the nationwide afforestation efforts to improve the
environment.
</P>
<P>
A total of 45 million hectares of trees have been planted in
China over the past few decades, making it the world's No. 1
planter of trees.
</P>
<P>
-- The annual conference of the China Association for Science
and Technology (CAST) was inaugurated Sunday in Xi'an, the
provincial capital of Shaanxi in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
About 5,000 Chinese and overseas scientists attended the
meeting, including more than 60 members of the Chinese Academy of
Sciences and the Chinese Academy of Engineering.
</P>
<P>
China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- China has not adequately prepared itself for the challenges
of economic globalization expected after its entry into the World
Trade Organization (WTO), a senior government adviser warned.
</P>
<P>
-- An agreement has been signed on a mould prevention project
for the terracotta warriors and for other relevant relics in Xi'an
by the Terracotta Warriors and Horses Museum and Belgium-based
Janssen Pharmaceutical NV.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, a rescue group of experts from
China and Belgium will soon be established to control the erosion
of the priceless cultural relics caused by over 40 species of
mould. 
</P>
</TEXT>
