<HEADLINE> Xinhua International News Summary at 0100 GMT, September 18 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein on Sunday met with
visiting Saudi Arabian Prince and Emir of Riyadh province Salman
Bin Abdul Aziz Al Saud, the highest Saudi official to visit the
kingdom in years.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, King Abdullah affirmed the close brotherly
ties between the two countries and stressed Jordan's keenness to
further cement relations with Saudi Arabia in all fields, Jordan's
official news agency Petra reported. (Jordan-Saudi-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI -- U.N. Secretary General's special envoy Catherine
Bertini arrived here on Sunday for a week-long tour over the
drought situation in Kenya and Ethiopia, the two worst-affected
countries in the Horn of Africa.
</P>
<P>
As a follow-up to her regional tour to the Horn of Africa in
April, Bertini will meet government officials, relief agencies and
drought-stricken communities in the two countries as part of her
review of the ongoing crisis which threatens the lives of more
than 14 million people in the region. (Kenya-U.N.-Tour)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- For the first time since 1992, Britain's
Conservatives have taken the lead over Labor in a national opinion
poll.
</P>
<P>
A poll by MORI published in the News of World on Sunday gave
the Conservatives a two point lead over New Labor, while a second
poll published in The Sunday Times by NOP puts Labor and the
Tories neck and neck. (UK-Conservatives-Labor)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- The South African government Sunday launched 13
poverty alleviation projects worth 11 million rand (about 1.6
million U.S. dollars) in the Northern KwaZulu-Natal region.
</P>
<P>
The projects, launched by Minister of Public Works Stella
Sigcau, are all labor intensive and will provide jobs while
constructing necessary infrastructure, said a statement from the
Department of Public Works. (SAfrica-Poverty-Projects)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- Seven people were killed in a car accident near
Pretoria Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
The accident, on the road between Brits and Rosslyn, involved a
lorry and a bakkie carrying passengers, said South African police
spokeswoman for the Marico area of North West province Sergeant
Erika Roos.
</P>
<P>
She said the seven people killed, including two children, were
members of an extended family who had been attending a gathering
together. (SAfrica-Road Accident) 
</P>
</TEXT>
