<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0383 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Champion Martin off to Good Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- World champion Camilla Martin
of Denmark started her second Olympic badminton campaign Sunday
and after a nervous start took only 19 minutes to beat Ellen
Angelinawaty of Indonesia 11-6, 11-2.
</P>
<P>
Kelly Morgan of Britain also started nervously against Koon Wai
Chee of China's Hong Kong, losing the first game 8-11. But after
a tactical talk by coach Chris Rees, Morgan played with more
patience and growing confidence to win 11-1, 11-1.
</P>
<P>
Top seed Gong Zhichao of China was impressive in her defeat of
Ling Wanting of China's Hong Kong, but it was not so easy for
former world champion Ye Zhaoying of China, who struggled to beat
Judith Meulendijks of the Netherlands in three games.
</P>
<P>
It was a good day for the Dutch who produced one of the biggest
upsets in the mixed doubles when Chris Bruil and Erica van den
Heuvel beat the former world champions Liu Yong and Ge Fei from
China.
</P>
<P>
The eight seeds in the men's doubles progressed to the
quarterfinals, but Olympic champions Ricky Ahmad Subagja and Rexy
Mainaky of Indonesia survived a scare against Martin Lundgaard
Hansen and Lars Paaske of Denmark before winning in three games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000918.0384 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Badminton Men's Singles Stars in Action Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The stars of the badminton's
men's singles competition take to the courts Monday for their
first taste of action in the Sydney 2000 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
Number one seed Taufik Hidayat of Indonesia sets out on his
quest to become badminton's youngest gold medalist when he plays
Yamada Hidetaka of Japan in their opening game.
</P>
<P>
Hidayat's compatriot Hendrawan, at number two, will play Tam
Kai Chuen of China's Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Olympic champion and sixth seed Poul-Erik Hoyer of Denmark
faces the possibly toughest task when he plays world champion Sun
Jun of China, who is unseeded in this competition.
</P>
<P>
At the age of 35, Hoyer is not finding the 25-year-old any
easier to handle. Sun Jun won seven of the pair's last nine
encounters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
