<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll Meets van Almsick in Historic Quest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rica's first ever
Olympic swimming gold medalist Claudia Poll will begin the task of
becoming the first woman to win back-to-back 200m freestyle
Olympic gold medals on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Poll took gold in Atlanta and is still the favorite to do so
again in Sydney despite the fact local hero Susie O'Neill has the
fastest time in the world so far this year. Poll's best for 2000
is 1:58.02, some 0.50 seconds behind 1:57.47 of O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
The women's 200m freestyle became an Olympic event at the 1968
Mexico Olympic Games and since then no swimmer has taken the event
at successive Games. Germany's Franziska van Almisick has
finished with two silver medals in 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
Poll has made no secret of the fact she wants to break van
Almsick's world record of 1:56.78 set at the 1994 Rome world
championships, where she originally failed to make the final but
gained a lane following the withdrawal of another German swimmer.
Poll's personal best is 1:57.48 swam at the 1997 Pan Pacific
championships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
