<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Sharpshooter Aims at Third Olympic Gold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SYDNEY, September 18 (Xinhua) -- German shooting star Ralf
Schumann will attempt to win his third Olympic gold medal when he
competes in the men's 25m rapid fire pistol on September 21.
</P>
<P>
Schumann, who has dominated the men's rapid fire event since
1987, won the gold medal at the Atlanta and Barcelona Olympic
Games, and silver at the Seoul Games.
</P>
<P>
Known as "Mr RApid Fire", the 38-year-old Schumann holds att
current world and Olympic records for the event.
</P>
<P>
Leading to the 2000 Sydney Olympic Games, Schumann won all of
the three World Cup event he competed in. These wins in Sydney,
Milan and Munich made him favorite to take out the gold medal.
</P>
<P>
"If you want to make a third medal in an Olympics there is
always a lot of pressure. In swimming and athletics it happens
sometimes but in shooting it is extremely rare," said Schumann. "
No matter how much work a person puts into the event once the top
eight qualifers make it to a final anything can happen."
</P>
<P>
Schumann said his main rivals are teammate Daniel Leonhard, who
has performed well in recent World Cups and Vladimir Vokhmyanin of
Kazakhstan who won bronze medals at the Atlanta and Barcelona
Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
The rapid fire requires an athlete to shoot at five targets in
eight, six and four seconds. It is a demanding sport and athletes
must be able to keep focused throughout the event and have quick
hand eye co-ordination. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
