<HEADLINE> UAE Protests Iraqi Media Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 18 (Xinhua) -- The United Arab Emirates has
officially protested to Iraq for its media attack on a statement
made by the UAE delegation at the U.N. Millennium Summit in New
York more than a week ago.
</P>
<P>
Saif Saeed bin Sa'ed, under secretary of the Foreign Ministry,
Monday summoned Iraq's charge D'affaires Abdul Raziq Hamoudi to
informed him of the "resentment and concern" of the UAE at the "
audacious remarks made by the Iraqi media," the official news
agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Some Iraqi newspapers have leveled charges against the UAE that
it did not mention the Iraqi issue in its statement released at the
Millennium Summit, and abused the head of the UAE delegation
personally.
</P>
<P>
"Such remarks will not serve relations between the two
countries, especially when the UAE has never ceased from calling to
lift the sanctions and alleviate the suffering of Iraqi people and
was the first to resume relations with Iraq," said Bin Sa'ed.
</P>
<P>
He also asked the Iraqi diplomat to ask his government to
refrain from this action which "runs in contradiction with the
simplest rules of bilateral relations."
</P>
<P>
The squabble cast a shadow over their newly resumed relations
which had been cut since the 1991 Gulf War. The two Gulf Arab
neighbors have just reopened their embassies in each other's
capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
