<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Puts Embargo on Products From Quarantine Area </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 18 (Xinhua) -- An embargo prohibiting
the movement of any agricultural produce from Camperdown area in
KwaZulu-Natal midlands of South Africa took effect Monday to
prevent spread of the foot and mouth disease.
</P>
<P>
The embargo affects agricultural produce from farms within a 10
kilometer radius of a pig farm, where the break-out occurred last
week, said Graham Linscott, a government official.
</P>
<P>
He regretted that the move might spell out as an economic
disaster for farmers in the area. About 100 farms have been
rounded into the quarantine zone.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the event, South Africa's Agricultural Minister
Thoko Didiza urged farmers in the area to adhere to the strict
measures, despite the disastrous result.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that spread of the disease to other parts of the
country could result in a national crisis.
</P>
<P>
Foot and mouth disease is also an international trade
sensitive disease and failure to contain it to a small area could
result in many countries imposing bans on agricultural exports
from South Africa, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Veterinary experts were sent to the area to kill more than 600
pigs by Monday morning, media reports said.
</P>
<P>
The reports also quoted experts as saying that the current
strain of disease might be coming from foreign countries like
Thailand, India or the Middle East where it was prevalent, because
the strain of disease had never occurred in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
It had been established that the virus was present in kitchen
refuse, which is a major source of pigfood, bought from a ship
docking in the Durban harbor, according to the reports.
</P>
<P>
Accordingly, the South African government on Sunday ordered
port authorities at the country's major harbors not to allow any
kitchen refuse to enter the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
