<HEADLINE> Boeing 737-700 Performs Demonstration Flights at China's Challenging Airports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 18 (Xinhua) -- A Boeing next-generation
737-700 performed demonstration flights last week at two of the
world's most challenging airports in China, the Seattle airplane
manufacturer said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The demonstration, simulating one inoperative engine on takeoff
and landing at both airports, Lhasa and Bangda in the Tibetan
highlands, was performed in cooperation with China Southwest
Airlines and the Civil Aviation Administration of China (CAAC). It
established the performance capabilities of the next-generation
737 for potential service in China's developing Western region,
Boeing said.
</P>
<P>
Boeing quoted one of its flight test pilots, Leon Robert, as
saying that "the flights went very well." "These high-altitude
airports are surrounded by steep, mountainous terrain," Robert
said. "We've clearly shown that the next-generation 737 payload
capability can meet the anticipated demands as well as meet all
the CAAC regulatory requirements for operations at these airports.
"
</P>
<P>
Lhasa is located at 3,566 meters above sea level, and Bangda
which, at 4,328 meters above sea level, is the highest commercial
airport in the world. Boeing said that prior to the trip to China,
Robert flew the mission in an engineering flight simulator
equipped with the database and terrain visuals for the two
airports. This enabled the team to gather aerodynamic data to
predict how the airport would perform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
